The screens attempt to capture different facets of ESG, such as compliance with international laws, relations with employees, and carbon emissions. The screens also exclude certain controversial businesses such as alcohol, tobacco, gambling, and weapons. The remaining firms are scored on ESG factors, and the top scoring firms within each sector (the top 50% by market cap) are selected for inclusion in the fund. NUDMs portfolio is weighted by a multifactor optimizer that tries to minimize any risk and return distortions created by the funds ESG screen. The portfolio is rebalanced and reconstituted quarterly. NUEM is a sibling fund with an emerging markets exposure.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the investment results, before fees and expenses, of the TIAA ESG International Developed Markets Equity Index (the "index"). In seeking to track the investment results of the index, the advisor attempts to replicate the index by investing all, or substantially all, of its assets in the securities represented in the index in approximately the same proportions as the index. The index identifies equity securities from the base index that satisfy certain ESG criteria, based on ESG performance data collected by MSCI ESG Research, Inc.
merged_description: This investment product seeks to track the performance of an index composed of equity securities from developed countries, excluding the United States and Canada, that meet certain environmental, social, and governance (ESG) criteria. It aims to achieve this by investing substantially all of its assets in the securities represented in the index in approximately the same proportions. The index construction begins by identifying companies from a broad developed markets universe and then applying various ESG screens. These screens capture positive ESG aspects, exclude controversial business activities such as alcohol, tobacco, gambling, and weapons, and ultimately select the top-scoring firms based on ESG factors within each sector (specifically the top 50% by market capitalization), using data from MSCI ESG Research. The resulting portfolio is weighted using a multifactor optimizer designed to mitigate risk and return distortions caused by the ESG screening process and is rebalanced quarterly.

name: KraneShares MSCI All China Health Care Index ETF
description_original: The fund will invest at least 80% of its net assets (plus borrowings for investment purposes) in instruments in its underlying index or in instruments that have economic characteristics similar to those in the underlying index. The underlying index is a free float adjusted market capitalization weighted index, subject to the 10/40 Constraint, which is designed to measure the equity market performance of Chinese companies in the healthcare sector. The fund is non-diversified.
description_eftcom: KURE holds all types of publicly-issued shares (including A-shares, B-shares, H-shares, N-shares, P-chips, and Red chips) of large- and mid-cap Chinese companies in the healthcare sector. Stocks must meet minimum trading and liquidity requirements and be classified in the healthcare sector under MSCIs GICS standard. Holdings are market cap-weighted with an adjustment based on the proportion of shares available to foreign investorsexcept for A-shares, which are treated as 100% available. Weights are also modified using a 10/40 capping methodology. Overall, KURE provides exposure to a relatively small slice of the Chinese economy. The index is rebalanced quarterly.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to provide investment results that, before fees and expenses, track the price and yield performance of the MSCI China All Shares Health Care 10/40 Index. The fund will invest at least 80% of its net assets (plus borrowings for investment purposes) in instruments in its underlying index or in instruments that have economic characteristics similar to those in the underlying index. The underlying index is a free float adjusted market capitalization weighted index, subject to the 10/40 Constraint, which is designed to measure the equity market performance of Chinese companies in the healthcare sector. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This fund seeks to track an index designed to measure the equity market performance of Chinese companies in the healthcare sector by investing at least 80% of its assets in index securities or those with similar characteristics. The underlying index includes large- and mid-cap healthcare companies across various publicly-issued share types (including A, B, H, N, P, and Red chips) that meet specific classification, trading, and liquidity requirements. The index is market cap-weighted, adjusted for free float (treating A-shares as fully available), and modified by a 10/40 capping methodology; it is rebalanced quarterly. As a non-diversified fund, it provides focused exposure to this specific segment of the Chinese equity market.

name: Roundhill Magnificent Seven ETF
description_original: The fund is an actively managed exchange-traded fund (“ETF”) that pursues its investment objective by seeking investment exposure to the largest companies (“Underlying Issuers”) in one or more of the following industries, each of which is defined by an independent industry classification scheme: Technology Hardware Industry; E-Commerce Discretionary Industry; Internet Media & Services Industry; and Software Industry (collectively, the “Technology Industries”). The fund is non-diversified.
description_eftcom: MAGS, at the time of launch, is the first-ever FAAMG ETF in the US market space. The fund targets a narrow portfolio of 5-10 stocks publicly known as tech giants, aiming to capture the largest companies in social media, e-commerce, consumer discretionary, cloud computing, tech hardware, and software. On an annual basis, the adviser reviews the US tech universe to select the largest companies based on market cap, trading volume, and sector relevance. Holdings are equally weighted in the portfolio and rebalanced quarterly. As an actively managed fund, the adviser has full discretion in managing the portfolio. From time to time, 100% of the funds assets may be invested in US treasury securities, money market funds, and/or short-term bond ETFs. Holdings may include common stocks and ADRs, though the fund primarily gains exposure through the use of swaps and forward contracts. Prior to Nov. 9, 2023, the fund was called Roundhill BIG Tech ETF, trading under the ticker BIGT.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks growth of capital. The fund is an actively managed exchange-traded fund (“ETF”) that pursues its investment objective by seeking investment exposure to the largest companies (“Underlying Issuers”) in one or more of the following industries, each of which is defined by an independent industry classification scheme: Technology Hardware Industry; E-Commerce Discretionary Industry; Internet Media & Services Industry; and Software Industry (collectively, the “Technology Industries”). The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This actively managed ETF seeks capital growth by targeting a non-diversified, narrow portfolio, typically consisting of 5-10 of the largest technology companies in the United States. Focusing on industries such as Technology Hardware, E-Commerce, Internet Media & Services, and Software, the adviser selects companies annually from the US tech universe based on criteria including market capitalization, trading volume, and sector relevance. The selected holdings are equally weighted and rebalanced on a quarterly basis. While the fund primarily gains investment exposure through the use of swaps and forward contracts, it may also hold common stocks and ADRs, and can temporarily invest up to 100% of its assets in cash equivalents like U.S. Treasury securities, money market funds, or short-term bond ETFs.

name: Defiance Connective Technologies ETF
description_original: The fund uses a passive management approach to track the total return performance, before fees and expenses, of the index. The index is a rules-based index that consists of a tiered, modified market capitalization-weighted portfolio of the U.S.-listed equity securities, including depositary receipts, of companies that derive at least 50% of their revenues from business activities, products, or services.
description_eftcom:
SIXG tracks an index of US-listed companies involved in the rollout of connective technologies. Investments consist of 50 companies, selected and weighted based on market capitalization.

SIXG focuses on US-listed equities tied to the development and deployment of connective technologies, such as 5G or 6G networks. The portfolio consists of 50 securities deriving at least 50% of their revenues from activities, products, or services, such as core cellular network equipment, REITs and MNOs, service assurance and network optimization, and enhanced mobile broadband and related infrastructure. The fund uses a modified market cap-weighted approach with a max weight of 5% per security. The index only selects the largest three REITs and MNOs with a cap of 1.5%. Rebalancing and reconstitution are done semi-annually. SIXG was the first ETF to offer broad exposure to 5G-related opportunities, trading as Defiance Next Gen Connectivity ETF with the ticker FIVG, until it was changed on July 22, 2024. In addition, on Sep. 23, the index changed its name from BlueStar 5G Communications Index to better represent its updated exposure.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the total return performance, before fees and expenses, of the Bluestar ® Connective Technologies Index (the index). The fund uses a passive management approach to track the total return performance, before fees and expenses, of the index. The index is a rules-based index that consists of a tiered, modified market capitalization-weighted portfolio of the U.S.-listed equity securities, including depositary receipts, of companies that derive at least 50% of their revenues from business activities, products, or services.
merged_description: The ETF employs a passive management approach to track the total return performance, before fees and expenses, of a rules-based index focused on US-listed companies involved in the rollout and deployment of connective technologies. The index selects approximately 50 US equity securities, including depositary receipts, based on criteria requiring companies to derive at least 50% of their revenues from related business activities, products, or services, such as core network equipment, infrastructure, and enhanced mobile broadband. The portfolio uses a tiered, modified market capitalization-weighting scheme, which includes individual security weight caps (e.g., a maximum 5% cap per security and a 1.5% cap for certain REITs and MNOs). The index is reconstituted and rebalanced semi-annually.

name: JPMorgan U.S. Minimum Volatility ETF
description_original: The fund will invest at least 80% of its assets in securities included in the underlying index. "Assets" means net assets, plus the amount of borrowing for investment purposes. The underlying index measures the performance of U.S. equity securities selected using a rules-based process that is designed so the underlying index targets lower volatility than the Russell 1000 Index.
merged_description: This ETF seeks to provide exposure to U.S. equity securities chosen via a rules-based selection process. The fund commits at least 80% of its assets, including any borrowed funds, to invest in securities included in its underlying index. This index is specifically constructed to target lower volatility compared to the Russell 1000 Index, thereby reflecting the ETF's strategy of focusing on less volatile U.S. stocks.

name: First Trust Global Tactical Commodity Strategy Fund
description_original: The fund is an actively managed exchange-traded fund ("ETF") that seeks to achieve attractive risk adjusted returns by investing in commodity futures contracts, exchange-traded commodity linked instruments, and commodity linked total return swaps (collectively, "Commodities Instruments") through a wholly-owned subsidiary of the fund organized under the laws of the Cayman Islands (the "Subsidiary"). The advisor expects to gain exposure to these investments exclusively by investing in the Subsidiary.
description_eftcom: FTGC brought active management to the commodities space. The fund doesn't directly own futures contracts, but gains exposure to commodities through its holdings in a Cayman Islands-based subsidiary which holds futures contracts. The fund can also short futures, hold commodity ETFs, and structured products tied to commodities. Since the fund limits its holding in the subsidiary to 25%, it aims to qualify as a regulated investment company and is structured as a 1940 Act open-ended fund, as opposed to a commodities pool. Overall it doesn't look much like a front-month GSCI benchmark. Its sector biases can swing far from neutral exposure. Its cash-only creation structure makes things simple for larger investors. FTGCs structure means that it intends to be taxed like other equity funds, and does not distribute K-1 forms to its investors.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to provide total return by providing investors with commodity exposure while seeking a relatively stable risk profile. The fund is an actively managed exchange-traded fund ("ETF") that seeks to achieve attractive risk adjusted returns by investing in commodity futures contracts, exchange-traded commodity linked instruments, and commodity linked total return swaps (collectively, "Commodities Instruments") through a wholly-owned subsidiary of the fund organized under the laws of the Cayman Islands (the "Subsidiary"). The advisor expects to gain exposure to these investments exclusively by investing in the Subsidiary.
merged_description: This actively managed ETF aims for total return and attractive risk-adjusted results in commodities while seeking a relatively stable risk profile. It primarily gains exposure to commodity futures, linked instruments, and swaps through a wholly-owned Cayman Islands subsidiary, rather than directly owning futures. The fund can also utilize other commodity-linked investments like ETFs and structured products. It does not track a traditional commodity benchmark and allows for tactical shifts in sector exposure. A key feature is its structure as a 1940 Act open-ended fund aiming for Regulated Investment Company status, achieved partly by limiting direct investment in the subsidiary, which distinguishes it from a commodity pool. This structure offers tax benefits similar to equity funds, avoiding K-1 distributions, and allows for simplified cash-only creations.

name: First Trust FTSE EPRA/NAREIT Developed Markets Real Estate Index Fund
description_original: The fund will normally invest at least 90% of its net assets (including investment borrowings) in the common stocks and depositary receipts that comprise the index. The index is modified market cap weighted based on free float market capitalization and includes the securities of real estate companies or REITs that are publicly traded on an official stock exchange located in North America, Europe or Asia and provides an audited annual report in English.
description_eftcom:
DTRE tracks an index of real estate stocks that support wired and wireless communication, data infrastructure, warehouses, and fulfillment centers. Selection and weighting of securities are based on three-month average trading values.

DTRE is a passively managed fund that provides exposure to real estate stocks perceived to support disruptive technology. It includes advanced wired and wireless communication, data storage and processing infrastructure, e-commerce warehouses, and fulfillment centers. The portfolio holds operating companies and REITs that derive at least 50% of revenues from owning, operating and/or leasing real estate that support rapid data transfer, distributed data handling, and e-commerce warehousing. Stocks must be listed on major globally recognized exchanges that meet sector, market-cap, and liquidity requirements. Holdings are weighted by their three-month average daily trading values, with a 10% single security cap. The index is reconstituted and rebalanced quarterly. Prior to Oct. 3, 2022, the fund was called First Trust FTSE EPRA/NAREIT Developed Markets Real Estate Index Fund, the first ETF to offer real estate exposure focused on developed markets worldwide, trading under the ticker FFR.
merged_description: This passively managed fund provides exposure to real estate companies and REITs that own, operate, or lease properties supporting disruptive technology themes, including advanced wired and wireless communication, data infrastructure, and e-commerce warehousing and fulfillment centers. It invests in publicly traded companies on major global exchanges in developed markets across North America, Europe, and Asia, focusing on securities where at least 50% of revenues are derived from these specific real estate activities. Portfolio holdings are weighted based on their three-month average trading values, subject to a single security cap, and the index is rebalanced quarterly.

name: WisdomTree Global High Dividend Fund
description_original: The fund will invest at least 95% of its total assets in component securities of the index and investments that have economic characteristics that are substantially identical to the economic characteristics of such component securities. The index is a fundamentally weighted index that is comprised of high dividend-yielding companies selected from the WisdomTree Global Dividend Index, which defines the dividend-paying universe of companies in the U.S., developed countries and emerging markets throughout the world. The fund is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
DEW tracks an index of the top 30% of global dividend-paying stocks ranked by dividend yield and weighted by dividends.

DEW offers exposure to a global range of high dividend-yielding companies. The selection universe is drawn from the Wisdom Tree Global Dividend Index. The fund selects stocks by dividend yield, picking the top 30% from its universe, with some adjustments based on fundamental valuation, quality and momentum factors. It then weights the winners by total dividends paid out in cash over the past 12 months, capping sector and country weights at 25%. The resulting basket of stocks favors US stocks and the financial sector, but most peer funds share these traits. The index is reconstituted annually.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the price and yield performance of the WisdomTree Global High Dividend Index. The fund will invest at least 95% of its total assets in constituent securities of the index and investments that have economic characteristics that are substantially identical to the economic characteristics of such constituent securities. The index is a fundamentally weighted index that is comprised of high dividend-yielding companies selected from the WisdomTree Global Dividend Index, which defines the dividend-paying universe of companies in the U.S., developed countries and emerging markets throughout the world. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This fund seeks to track an index comprised of high dividend-yielding companies sourced from a global universe of dividend payers spanning the U.S., developed, and emerging markets. The underlying index is fundamentally weighted, selecting securities from the top dividend yielders in the eligible universe, with potential adjustments based on fundamental factors. Constituent companies are weighted based on the total cash dividends paid over the preceding twelve months, subject to sector and country concentration caps. The fund typically invests at least 95% of its total assets in securities that are components of this index or possess substantially similar economic characteristics. It is classified as non-diversified.

name: SPDR S&P Global Infrastructure ETF
description_original: The SPDR S&P Global Infrastructure ETF seeks to provide investment results that, before fees and expenses, correspond generally to the total return performance of the S&P Global Infrastructure Index (the “Index”)Seeks to provide exposure to the 75 largest infrastructure-related stocks based on float-adjusted market cap and liquidityIndex is diversified across transportation, utilities, and energy infrastructure sub-industries
description_eftcom:
GII tracks a market-cap-weighted index of 75 infrastructure companies from developed and emerging markets engaged in the energy, transportation, or utility sectors.

GII tracks an index of 75 of the largest infrastructure firms globally, with constraints to ensure diversification between the energy, transportation, and utility sectors. The fund first selects the 15 largest emerging market companies from its eligible universe, limited to 10 per sector. These stocks must trade on a developed-market exchange. GII then rounds out its portfolio with the largest eligible developed-market companies such that the final portfolio consists of 30 transportation companies, 30 utility companies, and 15 energy companies. The transportation and utility sectors get 40% weight each, with energy getting 20%. Stocks are cap-weighted within each bucket, with no individual security having a weight greater than 5%. The funds small basket means that positions can change significantly at each semi-annual rebalance.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks investment results that, before fees and expenses, correspond generally to the total return performance of the S&P Global Infrastructure Index. The fund generally invests substantially all, but at least 80%, of its total assets in the securities comprising the index and in depositary receipts based on securities comprising the index. The index is comprised of 75 of the largest publicly listed infrastructure companies that meet specific investability requirements.
merged_description: This fund aims to provide investment results that correspond generally to the total return performance of a global infrastructure index, before fees and expenses. It typically invests substantially all, but at least 80%, of its assets in the securities comprising this index and in depositary receipts based on those securities. The index is composed of 75 of the largest publicly listed infrastructure companies worldwide, offering exposure across the transportation, utility, and energy sectors. It employs a specific selection and weighting methodology designed to ensure diversification among these sub-industries, targeting a set number of companies and weights for each sector based on factors including float-adjusted market capitalization and liquidity, and limiting individual security weightings. Due to the focused number of holdings, portfolio composition may shift notably at the semi-annual rebalance.

name: SPDR S&P Insurance ETF
description_original: The SPDR S&P Insurance ETF seeks to provide investment results that, before fees and expenses, correspond generally to the total return performance of the S&P Insurance Select Industry Index (the “Index”)Seeks to provide exposure to the insurance segment of the S&P TMI, which comprises the following sub-industries: Insurance Brokers, Life & Health Insurance, Multi-Line Insurance, Property & Casualty Insurance, and ReinsuranceSeeks to track a modified equal weighted index which provides the potential for unconcentrated industry exposure across large, mid and small cap stocksAllows investors to take strategic or tactical positions at a more targeted level than traditional sector based investing
description_eftcom:
KIE tracks an equal-weighted-index of insurance companies, as defined by GICS.

While KIE stays true to the definition of an insurance company, its selection universe and equal-weighting scheme narrows its stock universe to make a very different portfolio from the other funds in the segment. The fund underweights property and casualty insurance in favor of a large overweighting to reinsurance companies. It also reduces its concentration risk-- good news in a top-heavy sector. Overall, this fund is for those looking for unconventional exposure to the insurance sector.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to provide investment results that, before fees and expenses, correspond generally to the total return performance of an index that tracks the performance of publicly traded companies in the insurance industry. In seeking to track the performance of the S&P Insurance Select Industry Index (the "index"), the fund employs a sampling strategy. It generally invests substantially all, but at least 80%, of its total assets in the securities comprising the index. The index represents the insurance segment of the S&P Total Market Index ("S&P TMI").
merged_description: Designed to track a modified equal weighted index of companies within the insurance segment, this fund seeks to provide unconcentrated exposure across large, mid, and small-cap stocks. The index represents publicly traded insurance companies across various sub-industries including insurance brokers, life & health, multi-line, property & casualty, and reinsurance. By utilizing a modified equal weighting approach, the resulting portfolio differs significantly from market-cap weighted peers, potentially emphasizing areas like reinsurance while reducing exposure to property & casualty and mitigating concentration risk in a sector often dominated by a few large companies. It represents a targeted or unconventional way for investors to access the insurance industry.

name: Vanguard International High Dividend Yield Index Fund Admiral Shares
description_original: The fund invests by sampling the index, meaning that it holds a broadly diversified collection of securities that, in the aggregate, approximates the full index in terms of key characteristics. The index focuses on companies located in developed and emerging markets, excluding the United States, that are forecasted to have above-average dividend yields.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the performance of FTSE All-World ex US High Dividend Yield Index that measures the investment return of non-U.S. companies that are characterized by high dividend yield. The fund invests by sampling the index, meaning that it holds a broadly diversified collection of securities that, in the aggregate, approximates the full index in terms of key characteristics. The index focuses on companies located in developed and emerging markets, excluding the United States, that are forecasted to have above-average dividend yields.
merged_description: This ETF seeks to provide investment exposure to high-dividend-yielding companies located in developed and emerging markets outside the United States. The fund aims to track the performance of an index that measures returns of such companies by investing through a sampling strategy, holding a diversified collection of securities designed to approximate the index's overall characteristics.

name: Roundhill Sports Betting & iGaming ETF
description_original: Under normal circumstances, at least 80% of the fund's net assets (plus borrowings for investment purposes) will be invested in securities issued by Sports Betting and iGaming Companies. The index tracks the performance of the common stock (or corresponding American Depositary Receipts ("ADRs") or Global Depositary Receipts ("GDRs")) of exchange-listed companies that earn revenue from online gaming ("iGaming"). The fund is non-diversified.
description_eftcom: BETZ is the second ETF by RoundHill investments and the first ETF to offer global passive exposure to sports betting and iGaming companies. This includes companies that are actively involved in analyzing sports events and wagering, as well as those involved with online betting. Eligible companies are scored from 1 to 4, depending on their involvement in the sports betting and iGaming industry, with companies deriving more than 50% of their revenue from the theme assigned the highest score of 4. Components are weighted in proportion to both their combined theme score and their free-float market capitalization, with higher theme scores receiving heavier tilt factors. The index is rebalanced and reconstituted annually in December. Prior to October 2, 2023, the fund tracked the Roundhill Sports Betting & iGaming Index.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the total return performance, before fees and expenses, of the Morningstar® Sports Betting & iGaming Select IndexSM. The index was developed by Morningstar, Inc. and is designed to provide pure exposure to sports and online betting themes. The fund will generally invest all, or substantially all, of its assets in the component securities of the index, but also may invest in investments that provide comparable exposure, including but not limited to depositary receipts representing Index components and investments in other ETFs. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This ETF seeks to provide focused exposure to the global sports betting and iGaming industry by tracking a specialized index designed for pure exposure to these themes. It generally invests at least 80% of its assets in the securities of exchange-listed companies that derive significant revenue from activities such as online gaming, sports wagering, and related analysis. The index selects and weights components based on their revenue concentration in the theme and market capitalization, tilting towards companies with higher theme-related revenue. The fund is non-diversified and may utilize depositary receipts or other similar investments to achieve its objective. The underlying index is typically rebalanced annually.

name: WisdomTree Europe Quality Dividend Growth Fund
description_original: At least 80% of the fund's total assets will be invested in component securities of the index and investments that have economic characteristics that are substantially identical to the economic characteristics of such component securities. The index consists of dividend-paying common stocks of companies with growth characteristics that are incorporated and listed on a stock exchange in one of the following countries: Germany, Switzerland, United Kingdom, etc. The fund is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
EUDG tracks an index of companies in developed Europe, selected for growth characteristics and weighted by total dividends paid.

EUDG screens 300 developed Europe stocks, based on combined ranking of growth and quality factors. Index selection starts with EUDGs parent index WisdomTree International Equity Index. Growth factor ranking uses long-term earnings growth expectations, while the quality factor ranking is based on three year historical averages for ROE and ROA. Index weighting is based on the total regular cash dividends paid by all the companies in the Index over the prior annual cycle, heavily weighting those paying more. Issuers are capped at 5% and the maximum weight of any one sector or country is capped at 20% and 25%, respectively. The index is reconstituted annually. Prior to August 31, 2015, the WisdomTree Europe Quality Dividend Growth Index was named the WisdomTree Europe Dividend Growth Index.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the price and yield performance, before fees and expenses, of the WisdomTree Europe Quality Dividend Growth Index. At least 80% of the fund's total assets will be invested in constituent securities of the index and investments that have economic characteristics that are substantially identical to the economic characteristics of such constituent securities. The index consists of dividend-paying common stocks of companies with growth characteristics that are incorporated and listed on a stock exchange in one of the following countries: Germany, Switzerland, United Kingdom, etc. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This investment aims to mirror the performance of an index focused on dividend-paying companies in developed Europe selected for their growth and quality characteristics. The index identifies companies using factors like long-term earnings growth expectations, ROE, and ROA. It then weights constituents primarily based on the total cash dividends they pay, favoring higher dividend payers. To manage concentration, the index imposes caps on individual issuer, sector, and country weights. The fund maintains at least 80% of its assets in securities of this index or those with similar economic profiles and operates as a non-diversified fund.

name: FlexShares International Quality Dividend Defensive Index Fund
description_original: The underlying index is designed to reflect the performance of a selection of companies that, in aggregate, possess greater financial strength and stability characteristics relative to the Northern Trust International Large Cap Index. The fund will invest at least 80% of its total assets in the securities of the underlying index and in ADRs and GDRs based on the securities in the underlying index.
description_eftcom:
IQDE tracks an index of non-US companies from developed and emerging markets, selected and weighted by dividend payments and various fundamentals. The index aims for lower market risk (beta).

The security is being delisted. The last day of trading on an exchange is January 21, 2025. IQDE delivers a safe and sound portfolio by combining three investment aims: lower market risk (the safe part), stable returns (quality), and a strong dividend stream (the sound part). The index has a bias on large-caps by selecting its constituents from its Parent Index, Northern Trust International Large Cap Index, but it may also invest in mid-cap stocks. Securities ranking in the lowest quintile of quality and non-dividend paying firms are excluded. Quality is scored using a proprietary methodology based on management expertise (e.g. corporate finance activities), profitability, and cash flow. The remaining securities are optimized and weighted based on quality, dividend yield, and lower beta (0.5-1x than the Parent index). The Index is reconstituted quarterly starting each February. The fund was anticipated to merge into ticker: IQDF in June of 2023 but plans were canceled.
merged_description: This ETF aims to provide investors with a portfolio of non-US developed and emerging market companies characterized by lower market risk, stable returns, and a strong dividend stream, by tracking an index focused on financial strength and stability. The index selects constituents primarily from a large-cap international universe (potentially including mid-caps), excluding the lowest quality firms and non-dividend payers. Quality is determined via a proprietary methodology incorporating management, profitability, and cash flow. The index weights securities based on quality, dividend yield, and beta relative to a parent index, targeting a lower market risk profile. The fund invests at least 80% of assets in these index securities or equivalents, including ADRs and GDRs. Please note, the security is scheduled for delisting with January 21, 2025, as its last trading day.

name: Vanguard International Dividend Appreciation Index Fund Admiral Shares
description_original: The index focuses on high-quality companies located in developed and emerging markets, excluding the U.S., that have both the ability and the commitment to grow their dividends over time. The manager attempts to replicate the target index by investing all, or substantially all, of its assets in the collection of securities that make up the index, holding each stock in approximately the same proportion as its weighting in the index.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the performance of S&P Global Ex-U.S. Dividend Growers Index that measures the investment return of non-U.S. companies that have a history of increasing dividends. The index focuses on common stocks of high-quality companies located in developed and emerging markets, excluding the U.S., that have both the ability and the commitment to grow their dividends over time. The manager attempts to replicate the target index by investing all, or substantially all, of its assets in the collection of securities that make up the index, holding each stock in approximately the same proportion as its weighting in the index.
merged_description: This ETF seeks to track the performance of an index focusing on high-quality, non-U.S. companies in developed and emerging markets that have demonstrated a history and commitment to growing their dividends over time. The fund aims to replicate this index by investing substantially all its assets in the same securities in similar proportions.

name: iShares ESG Aware Conservative Allocation ETF
description_original: The fund is a fund of funds and seeks to achieve its investment objective by investing primarily in underlying funds that themselves seek investment results corresponding to their own respective underlying indexes each of which takes into account environmental, social and governance (“ESG”) characteristics. The underlying index is composed of a portfolio of underlying equity and fixed income funds with positive environmental, social, and governance characteristics intended to represent a conservative risk profile.
description_eftcom:
EAOK is an index-tracking fund-of-funds that tactically allocates 30/70 global equites and US investment grade bonds with positive ESG characteristics.

EAOK is part of iShares suite of target-risk strategies that screens for positive ESG traits. The fund invests exclusively in iShares ETFs aiming for exposure that is consistent with conservative risk tolerance. The index allocates its assets to four equity ETFs (ESGU, ESML, ESGD, ESGE) and one fixed income ETF (EAGG). The equity basket has a fixed 30% allocation and provides an all-cap exposure to developed and emerging markets securities, while the fixed income basket has a fixed 70% allocation to broad US investment grade bonds. The index rebalances semi-annually to realign the allocations. Prior to February 19, 2025, the fund name was iShares ESG Aware Conservative Allocation ETF.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the investment results of the BlackRock ESG Aware Conservative Allocation Index (the “underlying index”). The fund is a fund of funds and seeks to achieve its investment objective by investing primarily in underlying funds that themselves seek investment results corresponding to their own respective underlying indexes each of which takes into account environmental, social and governance (“ESG”) characteristics. The underlying index is composed of a portfolio of underlying equity and fixed income funds with positive environmental, social, and governance characteristics intended to represent a conservative risk profile.
merged_description: This is an index-tracking fund-of-funds designed to represent a conservative risk profile by investing primarily in underlying equity and fixed income funds. It seeks to achieve investment results consistent with an underlying index by investing exclusively in specific underlying ETFs. The strategy involves a fixed allocation of 30% to global equities, providing all-cap exposure across developed and emerging markets, and a fixed allocation of 70% to broad US investment grade bonds. A central component is the focus on positive environmental, social, and governance (ESG) characteristics, which the underlying funds and their respective indexes take into account. The fund rebalances semi-annually to maintain its target allocations.

name: BondBloxx JP Morgan USD Emerging Markets 1-10 Year Bond ETF
description_original: Under normal circumstances, the fund will invest at least 80% of its net assets (plus the amount of any borrowings for investment purposes) in emerging markets bonds with an average life of 1-10 years denominated in U.S. dollars, either directly or indirectly (e.g., through derivatives). It is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
XEMD tracks a market value-weighted index of USD-denominated debt issued by sovereign and quasi-sovereign issuers from emerging markets.

XEMD provides exposure to a basket of emerging market sovereign and quasi-sovereign bonds denominated in USD. The underlying index will include both investment-grade and high-yield securities with 1 to 10 years until maturity. Eligible countries must pass certain economic criteria. Convertible bonds are not eligible. By holding USD-denominated rather than local-currency debt, the fund eliminates direct currency risk for US investors but increases credit risk, as the strengthening dollar or weakening local currency could make debt harder to service. Each issuer must have at least USD 500 million outstanding, and bonds need at least 2.5 years remaining to maturity. The underlying index is market value-weighted and is rebalanced monthly on the last business day of the month.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the investment results of the J.P. Morgan EMBI Global Diversified Liquid 1-10 Year Maturity Index composed of U.S. dollar-denominated emerging market bonds with an average life of below 10 years. Under normal circumstances, the fund will invest at least 80% of its net assets in emerging markets bonds with an average life of 1-10 years denominated in U.S. dollars, either directly or indirectly. It is non-diversified.
merged_description: This ETF seeks exposure to a basket of U.S. dollar-denominated debt issued by sovereign and quasi-sovereign entities in emerging market countries. It tracks a market value-weighted index composed of these bonds, typically those with maturities ranging from 1 to 10 years, and includes both investment-grade and high-yield securities. The underlying index applies specific eligibility criteria regarding issuers, countries, and outstanding bond amounts. Investing in USD-denominated emerging market debt eliminates direct currency risk for U.S. investors but introduces increased credit risk influenced by U.S. dollar strength. The fund commits to investing at least 80% of its assets in such emerging market bonds and is classified as non-diversified. The index is rebalanced monthly.

name: Invesco S&P SmallCap Utilities & Communication Services ETF
description_original: The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise the index. Strictly in accordance with its guidelines and mandated procedures, S&P Dow Jones Indices, LLC compiles, maintains and calculates the index, which is designed to measure the performance of securities of small-capitalization U.S. companies in the utilities and communication services sectors, as defined by the Global Industry Classification Standard. The fund is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
PSCU tracks a market-cap-weighted index of small-cap US utilities and telecom services companies, selected from the S&P small-cap 600 Index universe.

PSCU delivers concentrated exposure to small-cap utilities and telecommunication services. Its portfolio thus differs markedly from the broader utilities universe, even beyond the obvious size tilt. PSCU typically overweights small natural gas utilities and underweights electric utilities, which are dominated by large-caps. It also includes telecoms, which our all-cap benchmark excludes. The fund typically holds just a handful of names, and offers some of the segments most concentrated exposure all in small-caps of course. For these reasons, PSCUs performance has differed materially from those of the typical large-cap-dominated utility ETFs.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the investment results (before fees and expenses) of the S&P SmallCap 600® Capped Utilities & Communication Services Index. The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise the index. Strictly in accordance with its guidelines and mandated procedures, S&P Dow Jones Indices, LLC compiles, maintains and calculates the index, which is designed to measure the performance of securities of small-capitalization U.S. companies in the utilities and communication services sectors, as defined by the Global Industry Classification Standard. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This ETF aims to track the investment results of the S&P SmallCap 600® Capped Utilities & Communication Services Index, which is designed to measure the performance of small-capitalization U.S. companies in the utilities and communication services sectors, as defined by the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS). Drawing its constituents from the S&P SmallCap 600 universe, the index is market-cap-weighted and capped. To achieve its objective, the fund generally invests at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise this index. This approach offers concentrated exposure to these specific small-cap segments, differing from broader utility benchmarks by typically overweighting small natural gas utilities, underweighting large electric utilities, and including telecoms. This results in a concentrated portfolio, often holding only a handful of names, and its performance can differ materially from large-cap-dominated utility ETFs. The fund is non-diversified.

name: SoFi Smart Energy ETF
description_original: The index follows a rules-based methodology that tracks the performance of the equity securities of publicly-traded large-, mid-, and small-capitalization U.S. and non-U.S. companies in developed and emerging markets that are selected based on a list of products and services that enable the practice of distributed energy generation. The fund will invest all, or substantially all, of its assets in the component securities that make up the index. It is non-diversified.
description_eftcom: The fund was delisted. The last day of trading on an exchange is February 20, 2024. ENRG provides exposure to global companies that support distributed energy resources (DER). The fund focuses on renewable energy sources, a subset of all possible DER solutions. Firms are screened to determine the percentage of revenue each company receives from DER compared to its total revenue by analyzing financial and sustainability reports, along with other publicly available information. Companies with at least 20% DER revenue or have at least a 10% increase in DER revenue over the prior year are considered, as well as those that disclose DER as a key revenue source. Companies are then screened for relevant sustainability and ESG standards. The index is reconstituted and rebalanced semi-annually, assigning each security an equal weight. Prior to February 14, 2022, the fund name was iClima Distributed Renewable Energy Transition Leaders ETF. Before August 9, 2022, the fund traded under the name iClima Distributed Smart Energy ETF and the ticker SHFT.
merged_description: This ETF, which ceased trading on February 20, 2024, pursued a strategy focused on investing in publicly-traded global companies involved in distributed energy resources, with a particular emphasis on renewable energy solutions. Covering large, mid, and small capitalization firms across developed and emerging markets, the fund tracked a rules-based index. Company selection involved screening based on revenue derived from these activities or providing products and services that enable distributed energy, further incorporating sustainability and ESG considerations. The index employed an equal weighting methodology and was reconstituted and rebalanced semi-annually. Considered non-diversified, the fund aimed to invest substantially all its assets in its component securities.

name: KraneShares Electric Vehicles and Future Mobility Index ETF
description_original: The fund will invest at least 80% of its net assets (plus borrowings for investment purposes) in instruments in its underlying index or in instruments that have economic characteristics similar to those in the underlying index. The index is designed to track the equity market performance of companies engaged in the production of electric vehicles or their components or in other initiatives that may change the future of mobility, as determined by index provider.
description_eftcom:
KARS tracks a modified market-cap-weighted index of stocks that are involved in the production of electric vehicles or other initiatives that may enhance future mobility.

KARS holds globally-listed stocks of companies that derive significant revenues from electric vehicles, energy storage technologies, autonomous navigation technology, lithium and copper mining, and hydrogen fuel cells. An index committee determines portfolio inclusion by scraping filings of proposed companies for thematic key terms and then back-testing the resulting basket. This gives a concentrated portfolio of about 32 companies that are market-cap-weighted, with weights of the top 8 securities capped at 5% and other securities at 2.5%. However, if the holdings are less than 32, equal-weighting may be applied. KARS uses representative sampling to track its index, which is reconstituted and rebalanced quarterly. Prior to June 16, 2021, the fund tracked the Solactive Electric Vehicles and Future Mobility Index.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to provide investment results that correspond to the price and yield performance of the Bloomberg Electric Vehicles Index. The fund will invest at least 80% of its net assets (plus borrowings for investment purposes) in instruments in its underlying index or in instruments that have economic characteristics similar to those in the underlying index. The index is designed to track the equity market performance of companies engaged in the production of electric vehicles or their components or in other initiatives that may change the future of mobility, as determined by index provider.
merged_description: This ETF tracks the Bloomberg Electric Vehicles Index, a modified market-cap-weighted index designed to follow companies engaged in the production of electric vehicles, their components, or other initiatives aimed at changing the future of mobility. This includes companies involved in energy storage technologies, autonomous navigation technology, lithium and copper mining, and hydrogen fuel cells. The fund invests at least 80% of its net assets in instruments in or with economic characteristics similar to those in its underlying index. Utilizing a selection process that identifies globally-listed companies with significant revenue exposure to these themes, the portfolio is relatively concentrated, typically holding around 32 companies. The weighting is market-cap based with caps on individual security weights (5% for the top 8, 2.5% for others), though equal weighting may apply if holdings fall below 32. The fund uses representative sampling to track the index, which is reconstituted and rebalanced quarterly.

name: First Trust NASDAQ ABA Community Bank Index Fund
description_original: The fund will normally invest at least 90% of its net assets (including investment borrowings) in the common stocks that comprise the index. The index is designed to track the performance of small, mid and large capitalization companies that comprise the community banking industry.
description_eftcom: QABA tracks an index of NASDAQ-listed US banks and thrifts while deliberately excluding the 50 largest based on asset size, according to Federal Deposit Insurance Corporation (FDIC) reports. QABA also excludes banks with an international specialization (assets greater than USD 10 billion and more than 25% of total assets in non-US offices) and banks with a credit card specialization (i.e. banks with credit card loans plus securitized receivables in excess of 50% of total assets plus securitized receivables). The result is an ETF that uniquely targets true community banks, avoiding the mega-money centers that tend to dominate this segment. The index is market-cap-weighted and undergoes quarterly rebalance and semi-annual reconstitution, subject to certain caps. The maximum weight of an issuer is capped at 25% and issuers weighting more than 5% in aggregate should not exceed 50% of the entire portfolio.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks investment results that correspond generally to the price and yield (before the fund's fees and expenses) of an equity index called the NASDAQ OMX® ABA Community Bank TM Index. The fund will normally invest at least 90% of its net assets (including investment borrowings) in the securities that comprise the index. The index is designed to track the performance of small, mid and large capitalization companies that comprise the community banking industry.
merged_description: This ETF tracks an index designed to provide exposure to the US community banking industry. It typically invests at least 90% of its assets in the common stocks included in this index, which comprises small, mid, and large-capitalization companies. A key feature is the index's methodology for defining "community banks"; it specifically targets NASDAQ-listed US banks and thrifts while excluding the 50 largest institutions by asset size, as well as banks with significant international operations or a concentration in credit card lending. This approach aims to avoid large money-center banks and focus on traditional community-oriented institutions. The index is market-cap-weighted, with quarterly rebalancing and semi-annual reconstitution subject to certain issuer caps.

name: Simplify Bitcoin Strategy PLUS Income ETF
description_original: The fund is an actively managed exchange-traded fund (an "ETF"). The fund's adviser seeks to achieve its investment objective by using three strategies: (1) a Bitcoin futures strategy, (2) an income strategy, and (3) an option overlay strategy. Even though the adviser employs three strategies, the fund's portfolio is composed primarily of income producing securities. It is non-diversified.
description_eftcom: MAXI pursues three distinct strategies: long exposure to Bitcoin futures, collateral management via short-term debt securities, and income generation through active option overlay strategies. The funds adviser allocates the total economic value of Bitcoin exposure to be 100% of the funds net assets. A Cayman Island subsidiary is used to hold Bitcoin futures. High-quality, short-term US Treasury securities, or similar ETF exposure, serves as collateral for the futures positions. Reverse repurchase agreements may be entered into to potentially increase income. In addition, up to 20% of the funds assets will be used in option overlay strategies. The core of the option strategies consists of writing exchange-traded put and call option spreads on securities, index futures, or ETFs that the funds adviser believes to be sufficiently correlated to Bitcoin futures. Generally, the option spreads selected are close to expiration and positions are actively traded.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks income and capital appreciation. The fund is an actively managed exchange-traded fund (an “ETF”). The fund’s adviser seeks to achieve its investment objective by using three strategies: (1) a Bitcoin strategy, (2) an income strategy, and (3) an option overlay strategy. Under normal market conditions, the adviser selects investments in Bitcoin related instruments so that the total value of economic Bitcoin exposure is approximately 50% to 200% of the net assets of the fund. It is non-diversified.
merged_description: This actively managed ETF seeks income and capital appreciation primarily through a combination of three strategies: gaining economic exposure to Bitcoin futures, managing collateral assets for income, and employing option overlays. The fund targets economic exposure to Bitcoin futures, typically around 100% of net assets, though this may range from approximately 50% to 200%, using a Cayman Island subsidiary to hold long futures positions. Income is generated by managing the collateral for these futures, largely consisting of high-quality, short-term US Treasury securities or similar ETFs, potentially enhanced by reverse repurchase agreements. Further income is sought via actively traded option overlay strategies, using up to 20% of assets to write exchange-traded put and call spreads on instruments correlated to Bitcoin futures. The fund is non-diversified.

name: First Trust RBA American Industrial RenaissanceTM ETF
description_original: The fund will normally invest at least 90% of its net assets (including investment borrowings) in the equity securities that comprise the index. The index is designed to measure the performance of small and mid cap U.S. companies in the industrial and community banking sectors.
description_eftcom:
AIRR tracks a multifactor-selected index of equities that can benefit from potential regain in market share of US industrial and community banking sector.

AIRR is passively managed to select large- and midcap US companies from the Russel 2500 with the following industries: Commercial Services & Supplies, Construction & Engineering, Electrical Equipment, Machinery, and Banks. Firms must also have a positive 12-months forward earnings consensus estimate to be considered in the index. AIRR excludes community banks outside traditional mid-western manufacturing hubs, like Pennsylvania, Wisconsin, Michigan, Ohio, Illinois, Indiana and Iowa. Firms with non-US sales of more than 25% are also excluded. The index is weighted using proprietary portfolio optimization method and ensures that Banks will have a 10% sector cap and issuers will not exceed a 4% weight. The Index is reconstituted and rebalanced quarterly.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks investment results that correspond generally to the price and yield (before the fund's fees and expenses) of an index called the Richard Bernstein Advisors American Industrial Renaissance ® Index (the "index"). The fund will normally invest at least 90% of its net assets (including investment borrowings) in the equity securities that comprise the index. The index is designed to measure the performance of small and mid cap U.S. companies in the industrial and community banking sectors.
merged_description: This passively managed ETF seeks investment results corresponding to an index by normally investing at least 90% of its net assets in the index's equity securities. The index tracks U.S. mid and small-cap companies primarily within the industrial and community banking sectors, aiming to capture the concept of an "American Industrial Renaissance." It focuses on specific industries such as Commercial Services & Supplies, Construction & Engineering, Electrical Equipment, Machinery, and Banks. Stock selection utilizes a multifactor approach, requiring positive forward earnings and applying exclusions like those for companies with substantial non-U.S. sales or community banks outside specific Midwest regions. The index employs a proprietary weighting optimization method with issuer and sector caps, and is reconstituted and rebalanced quarterly.

name: QRAFT AI-Enhanced U.S. High Dividend ETF
description_original: The fund is an actively-managed ETF that seeks to achieve its investment objective by utilizing an investment strategy enhanced by the use of artificial intelligence. The fund invests at least 80% of its net assets, plus the amounts of any borrowings for investment purposes, in dividend paying securities of U.S.-listed companies. A significant portion of the fund’s assets consisted of securities of companies in the consumer discretionary, consumer staples, and information technology sectors, although this may change from time to time. It is non-diversified.
merged_description: This actively-managed ETF seeks to achieve its investment objective through a strategy enhanced by the use of artificial intelligence. It focuses its investments primarily in dividend-paying securities of companies listed in the United States, allocating at least 80% of its net assets to such holdings. The fund has historically shown a significant concentration in companies operating within the consumer discretionary, consumer staples, and information technology sectors, though its sector allocation is subject to change. The fund operates as non-diversified.

name: First Trust Industrials/Producer Durables AlphaDEX Fund
description_original: The fund will normally invest at least 90% of its net assets (including investment borrowings) in the common stocks that comprise the index. The index is a modified equal-dollar weighted index to objectively identify and select stocks from the Russell 1000® Index in the industrials and producer durables sectors that may generate positive alpha relative to traditional passive-style indices through the use of the AlphaDEX® selection methodology.
description_eftcom:
FXR tracks an index of large- and mid-cap US industrial firms. The underlying index uses multi-factor selection and tiered equal-weighting.

FXR uses a quant-based model to select industrial stocks it believes will outperform the broad industrials sector. The funds tiered equal-weighting scheme tilts the fund toward mid-cap companies. Aside from considerably less exposure to some of the segment giants, FXR also has pronounced sector bets. Overall, the fund offers a smart beta approach to the US industrials space, instead of providing market-like exposure. The index is reconstituted and rebalanced on a quarterly basis.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks investment results that correspond generally to the price and yield (before the fund's fees and expenses) of an equity index called the StrataQuant® Industrials Index. The fund will normally invest at least 90% of its net assets (including investment borrowings) in the securities that comprise the index. The index is a modified equal-dollar weighted index to objectively identify and select stocks from the Russell 1000® Index in the industrials and producer durables sectors that may generate positive alpha relative to traditional passive-style indices through the use of the AlphaDEX® selection methodology.
merged_description: This ETF seeks to provide exposure to the U.S. industrials sector by tracking a specific equity index, normally investing at least 90% of its assets in the securities that compose it. The underlying index selects large- and mid-cap stocks from the Russell 1000® Index within the industrials and producer durables sectors using a quantitative, multi-factor selection methodology known as AlphaDEX®. This methodology aims to identify companies with the potential to generate positive alpha relative to traditional passive indices. The index employs a modified equal-dollar or tiered equal-weighting scheme, resulting in a tilt towards mid-cap companies and reduced exposure to sector giants compared to market capitalization-based approaches. This represents a smart beta strategy focused on potential outperformance rather than market-like representation within the U.S. industrials space, with the index undergoing quarterly reconstitution and rebalancing.

name: Invesco S&P 500 Equal Weight Utilities ETF
description_original: The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise the underlying index. The underlying index is composed of all of the components of the S&P 500® Utilities Plus Index, an index that contains the common stocks of all companies included in the S&P 500® Index that are classified as members of the utilities sector, as defined according to the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS).
description_eftcom:
RSPU tracks an equal-weighted index of S&P 500 utilities companies.

RSPU tracks an equal-weighted index of large-cap utilities companies. Its equal-weighting scheme skews it away from a market-like portfolio. The fund also includes a significant allocation to telecom stocks, which are not included in some utilities fund. This is common, however, as many utilities ETFs combine the two sectors and telecom stocks may pay higher dividends than utilities. Still, investors looking for pure-play exposure should look elsewhere. The index is rebalanced on a quarterly basis. Prior to June 07, 2023, the fund traded under the ticker, RYU.
merged_description: This ETF tracks the S&P 500 Utilities Plus Index, which comprises S&P 500 companies from the utilities sector, defined by GICS, along with a significant allocation to telecom stocks. A key feature is its equal-weighted strategy, differing from market-cap weighting, with the fund typically investing at least 90% of its assets in these securities. The underlying index undergoes quarterly rebalancing. This structure, including sectors beyond traditional utilities, means the fund is not a pure-play utilities investment.

name: Strive Mid-Cap ETF
description_original: The index measures the performance of the mid-capitalization sector in the U.S. equity market as determined by Bloomberg. Under normal circumstances, substantially all, but at least 80%, of the fund’s total assets will be invested in mid-capitalization companies.
description_eftcom:
STXM tracks an index of 400 US mid-cap stocks selected and weighted based on market capitalization.

STXM provides exposure to the US mid-cap space. Starting with a broad, total market universe of 1500 US stocks, the index selects securities ranked 501 to 900 by market capitalization. Eligible securities must be listed on a US exchange and have a free float of at least 10% of its total shares outstanding. The index includes common stock and real estate investment trusts. Selected securities are weighted by market capitalization. The fund intends to utilize a replication strategy, which means it will invest all of its assets in the securities comprising the index. However, the adviser may use a sampling strategy if it is determined to be in the best interest of shareholders. The index rebalances semi-annually in January and July.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the total return performance, before fees and expenses, of the Bloomberg US 400 Index. The index measures the performance of the mid-capitalization sector in the U.S. equity market as determined by Bloomberg. Under normal circumstances, substantially all, but at least 80%, of the fund’s total assets will be invested in mid-capitalization companies.
merged_description: This fund seeks to track the total return performance, before fees and expenses, of the Bloomberg US 400 Index, which measures the performance of 400 U.S. mid-capitalization stocks. Under normal circumstances, it invests substantially all, normally at least 80%, of its assets in mid-capitalization companies. The underlying index selects its constituents from the top 1500 U.S. stocks by market capitalization, specifically focusing on those ranked 501 through 900. Eligible securities must be listed on a U.S. exchange and have a free float of at least 10%; the index includes common stock and real estate investment trusts and weights securities by market capitalization. The fund intends to utilize a replication strategy, though sampling may be used, and the index rebalances semi-annually.

name: Goldman Sachs Dynamic California Municipal Income ETF
description_original: The fund invests, under normal circumstances, at least 80% of its net assets plus any borrowings for investment purposes in fixed income securities issued by or on behalf of the state of California and its political subdivisions, agencies and instrumentalities and other states, territories and possessions of the United States and the political subdivisions, agencies and instrumentalities thereof, the interest on which is exempt from regular federal income tax and California personal income tax. The fund is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
GCAL seeks a high level of current income by investing in municipal securities exempt from federal and California state income tax. The actively managed fund mainly holds investment grade bonds with a two- to eight-year duration.

GCAL utilizes an active approach to a niche segment of the US muni bond space. The fund generally holds USD-denominated muni bonds issued by the state of California and its political subdivisions, seeking interest income exempt from federal and California state income tax. The fund may allocate its assets entirely to private activity bonds, whose interest may be a preference item for the federal alternative minimum tax. It may also get exposure through affiliated or unaffiliated investment companies, including other ETFs. Despite its focus on investment grade bonds, the fund can invest up to 30% in non-investment-grade bonds and may purchase securities of issuers in default. In constructing the portfolio, the fund adviser incorporates both a top-down approach and a bottom-up analysis. As part of its fundamental selection process, the adviser may integrate ESG factors alongside traditional fundamental metrics. Typically, the portfolio duration will range between two and eight years.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks a high level of current income that is exempt from regular federal income tax and California personal income tax. The fund invests, under normal circumstances, at least 80% of its net assets plus any borrowings for investment purposes in fixed income securities issued by or on behalf of the state of California and its political subdivisions, agencies and instrumentalities and other states, territories and possessions of the United States and the political subdivisions, agencies and instrumentalities thereof, the interest on which is exempt from regular federal income tax and California personal income tax. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This ETF seeks a high level of current income that is exempt from regular federal income tax and California personal income tax. Under normal circumstances, it invests at least 80% of its net assets plus borrowings in fixed income securities issued by or on behalf of the state of California and other U.S. states, territories, and possessions, focusing on those whose interest qualifies for the specified tax exemptions. The actively managed portfolio typically holds investment grade bonds but can invest up to 30% in non-investment-grade securities, including those in default, and generally maintains a duration between two and eight years. Adopting a non-diversified approach, the fund incorporates both top-down and bottom-up analysis in portfolio construction.

name: Pacer BlueStar Engineering the Future ETF
description_original: A rules-based exchange traded fund (ETF) that aims to offer investors exposure to globally listed companies and depositary receipts that generate at least 50% of their revenues from robotics and manufacturing automation, 3D printing or computer aided design.
description_eftcom:
BULD tracks a modified market cap-weighted index of equities that provides global exposure to robotics and 3D printing.

BULD is passively managed to hold globally-listed stocks and depositary receipts of companies enabling the Fourth Industrial Revolution, particularly robotics and 3D printing. The index includes firms that derive at least 50% revenue from (i) robotics & manufacturing automation equipment, (ii) computer aided design (CAD) software, or (iii) 3D printing centers, hardware, software, and materials. The index selects at least 25 securities in the first sub-industry and at least 10 each in the other two sub-industries. The resulting portfolio is weighted in tiers, with robotics & manufacturing automation allocated 50% of the portfolio weight, while CAD and 3D printing are each given 25%. Securities are weighted by market capitalization within each tier, subject to an 8% single security capping. The aggregate weight of constituents with at least 5% weight is capped at 50%. The index is reconstituted and rebalanced semi-annually
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the total return performance, before fees and expenses, of the BlueStar Robotics and 3D Printing Index (the “index”). The index is a rules-based index that consists of globally-listed stocks and depositary receipts of companies that derive at least 50% of their revenues from Robotics and 3D Printing Companies, as determined by the index provider. The fund adviser will generally use a “replication” strategy to achieve its investment objective, meaning it will invest in all of the component securities of the index. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This passively managed fund seeks to provide global exposure to companies enabling the Fourth Industrial Revolution, focusing specifically on robotics, manufacturing automation, 3D printing, and computer aided design. It tracks a rules-based index composed of globally listed stocks and depositary receipts of companies that generally derive at least 50% of their revenue from these technological areas. The index employs a modified market capitalization weighting strategy, structuring the portfolio in tiers based on the specific technology categories with market cap weighting and concentration limits applied within those tiers. The fund typically uses a replication strategy to achieve its investment objective and is considered non-diversified.

name: Hartford Multifactor Low Volatility US Equity ETF
description_original: The investment seeks to provide investment results that, before fees and expenses, correspond to the total return performance of the Hartford Multifactor Low Volatility US Equity Index. The fund generally invests at least 80% of its assets in the equity securities that are components of the index. The index is designed to outperform a U.S. capitalization-weighted universe with up to 25% less volatility compared to that of the U.S. capitalization-weighted universe over a complete market cycle through the index construction process.
merged_description: Seeking to track the performance of a U.S. equity index, this investment product generally invests at least 80% of its assets in the index's component securities. The index is strategically designed to pursue lower volatility, targeting up to 25% less volatility compared to a U.S. capitalization-weighted universe over a complete market cycle, while also aiming to outperform that benchmark.

name: SPDR SSGA Multi-Asset Real Return ETF
description_original: The SPDR SSGA Multi-Asset Real Return ETF seeks to achieve real return consisting of capital appreciation and current income. Seeks to provide exposure to domestic and international inflation protected securities, real estate securities, commodities, infrastructure companies, and companies in natural resources and/or commodity businesses which may include agriculture, energy, and metals and mining companies as well as industrial, and utility companies.The investment process relies on a proprietary quantitative model as well as fundamental views regarding factors that may not be captured by the quantitative model
description_eftcom:
RLY is an actively-managed fund that attempts to hedge against inflation by investing in funds with exposure to real estate, commodities, TIPS and natural resources companies.

RLY aims to achieve real return consisting of capital appreciation and current income through a fund-of funds structure. The funds active manager considers real return to be a rate of return above the rate of inflation. RLY uses a proprietary quantitative models as well the fund advisers fundamental views on qualitative factors to allocate exposure across asset classes via ETFs, including equities from developed and emerging markets, government bonds, TIPs, commodities (through the use of derivatives) and REITs. In the fund advisers view, the funds allocation among these asset classes should be consistent with its stated goal.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to achieve real return consisting of capital appreciation and current income. Under normal circumstances, the Adviser invests at least 80% of the net assets of the fund among ETPs that provide exposure to the following primary asset classes: (i) inflation protected securities issued by the United States government; (ii) domestic and international real estate securities; (iii) commodities; (iv) publicly-traded domestic and international infrastructure companies; and (iv) publicly-traded companies in natural resources and/or commodities businesses.
merged_description: This actively-managed fund aims to provide real return, defined as a rate of return exceeding inflation, through capital appreciation and current income. It employs a fund-of-funds structure, primarily investing through exchange-traded products and other funds that offer exposure to various asset classes intended to hedge against inflation. Key exposures sought by the fund include U.S. inflation-protected securities (TIPS), domestic and international real estate securities, commodities, publicly-traded infrastructure companies, and businesses involved in natural resources and commodities, such as agriculture, energy, and metals and mining. The investment strategy relies on a proprietary quantitative model alongside the manager's fundamental qualitative views to allocate assets across these exposures.

name: WisdomTree India ex-State-Owned Enterprises Fund
description_original: Normally, at least 80% of the fund's total assets (exclusive of collateral held from securities lending) will be invested in component securities of the index and investments that have economic characteristics that are substantially identical to the economic characteristics of such component securities. The index is a modified float-adjusted market cap weighted index that consists of companies incorporated and traded in India, excluding common stocks of "state-owned enterprises." The fund is non-diversified.
description_eftcom: The security was delisted. The last day of trading on an exchange is October 20, 2023. The fund is closing. The last day of trading on an exchange is October 20, 2023. IXSE is designed around the premise that private corporations outperform firms controlled by governments. The fund aims to provide broad exposure to Indian companies, excluding state-owned enterprises (SOEs) that tend to dominate the telecommunications and transportation sectors. The fund defines an SOE as one with more than 20% government ownership. In addition, IXSE uses certain environmental, social and governance (ESG) criteria to filter securities. Holdings are market-cap-weighted with single security and sector weight caps at 10% and 30%, respectively. Although, the resulting portfolio may have some sector biases, loose guardrails prevent extreme departures from market-like exposure to any sector. The index is reconstituted and rebalanced annually.
merged_description: This investment product, which is now closing and has been delisted with its final trading day on October 20, 2023, was designed to offer exposure to Indian companies based on the concept that private corporations often outperform state-controlled entities. It specifically excluded State-Owned Enterprises (SOEs), defined by having over 20% government ownership, which frequently dominate sectors such as telecommunications and transportation. Additionally, it incorporated certain environmental, social, and governance (ESG) criteria.
