It seeks to capture US small-caps with high ESG scores within each GICS sector, while maintaining the sector weights of the S&P 600. The index uses exclusionary screens, filtering out companies (1) involved in tobacco, controversial weapons, and thermal coal, (2) falling in the bottom 5% of the United Nations Global Compact (UNGC) score ranking, or (3) falling in the bottom 25% of ESG scores within each GICS industry group. The remaining companies are ranked in descending order based on their ESG scores, with securities in the top 75% of market capitalization within each industry group selected for inclusion. To track the index, the fund employs a sampling strategy. The index is weighted by market capitalization and rebalances on an annual basis.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to provide investment results that, before fees and expenses, correspond generally to the total return performance of the S&P SmallCap 600 Scored & Screened Index. Under normal market conditions, the fund generally invests substantially all, but at least 80%, of its total assets in the securities comprising the index. The index is designed to measure the performance of securities meeting certain sustainability criteria, while maintaining similar overall industry group weights as the S&P SmallCap 600 Scored & Screened Index. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This ETF seeks to provide investment results corresponding generally to the total return performance of an index that is based on the S&P SmallCap 600 and incorporates environmental, social, and governance (ESG) criteria. The index filters out companies involved in specific controversial activities like tobacco, controversial weapons, and thermal coal, as well as those with low United Nations Global Compact scores or falling into the lowest quartile of ESG scores within their respective industry groups. It then selects companies based on their ESG scores and market capitalization within each industry. Designed to maintain similar sector and industry group weights as the broad S&P SmallCap 600 Index, the constituent securities are weighted by market capitalization, and the index rebalances annually. The fund typically invests substantially all of its assets in the index securities, employing a sampling strategy to track the index performance before fees and expenses. The fund is non-diversified and may serve as a potential ESG core exposure.

name: Vanguard Materials Index Fund Admiral Shs
description_original: The fund employs an indexing investment approach designed to track the performance of the MSCI US Investable Market Index (IMI)/Materials 25/50, an index made up of stocks of large, mid-size, and small U.S. companies within the materials sector, as classified under the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS). The Advisor attempts to replicate the target index by seeking to invest all, or substantially all, of its assets in the stocks that make up the index, in order to hold each stock in approximately the same proportion as its weighting in the index. The fund is non-diversified.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the performance of the MSCI US Investable Market Index (IMI)/Materials 25/50. The fund employs an indexing investment approach designed to track the performance of the index, an index made up of stocks of large, mid-size, and small U.S. companies within the materials sector, as classified under the GICS. The Advisor attempts to replicate the target index by seeking to invest all, or substantially all, of its assets in the stocks that make up the index, in order to hold each stock in approximately the same proportion as its weighting in the index. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This fund employs an indexing investment approach designed to track the performance of the MSCI US Investable Market Index (IMI)/Materials 25/50. This index is composed of large, mid-size, and small U.S. companies within the materials sector, classified under the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS). The fund seeks to replicate the target index by investing substantially all of its assets in the stocks that make up the index, holding each stock in approximately the same proportion as its weighting. As a result, the fund provides focused exposure to this segment of the U.S. market and is non-diversified.

name: iShares MSCI Kuwait ETF
description_original: The fund seeks to track the investment results of the MSCI All Kuwait Select Size Liquidity Capped Index (the “underlying index”), which is designed to measure the performance of the Kuwait equity universe. The underlying index is a free float-adjusted market capitalization weighted index with a capping methodology applied to avoid concentration. BFA uses a representative sampling indexing strategy to manage the fund. It may or may not hold all of the securities in the underlying index. The fund is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
KWT tracks a market-cap-weighted index of all-cap stocks in Kuwait.

KWT tracks an index that aims to provide broad exposure to companies headquartered or listed in Kuwait and carry out the majority of their operations in the area. The underlying index applies size and liquidity caps to the MSCI All Kuwait 30 Index. The index is market-cap weighted with large- and midcap companies being capped at 25% and all issuers with a weight above 5% do not cumulatively exceed 50% weight in the index. Small-cap companies and less liquid securities are represented at their weight as in the Parent Index, therefore not subject to capping. Investors should take note of sector exposure as this will change over time. The fund can concentrate its investments in a particular industry or group, which may or may not be energy.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the investment results of a broad-based equity index with exposure to Kuwait, as defined by the index provider. The fund seeks to track the investment results of the MSCI All Kuwait Select Size Liquidity Capped Index (the “underlying index”), which is designed to measure the performance of the Kuwait equity universe. The underlying index is a free float-adjusted market capitalization weighted index with a capping methodology applied to avoid concentration. BFA uses a representative sampling indexing strategy to manage the fund. It may or may not hold all of the securities in the underlying index. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This fund seeks to track a free float-adjusted market capitalization weighted index providing broad exposure to companies within the Kuwait equity universe. The underlying index incorporates a size and liquidity capping methodology, including limits on large and mid-cap securities and cumulative weights, while allowing small-caps to represent their full weight, specifically designed to manage concentration. The fund employs a representative sampling strategy and is considered non-diversified, potentially leading to concentration in specific sectors.

name: iShares MSCI Global Silver and Metals Miners ETF
description_original: The fund generally will invest at least 80% of its assets in the component securities of the underlying index and in investments that have economic characteristics that are substantially identical to the component securities of the underlying index. The index has been developed by MSCI Inc. (the "index provider" or "MSCI") to focus on approximately 25 companies in developed and emerging markets that are involved in silver mining or exploration. The fund is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
SLVP tracks a market-cap-weighted index of global companies that earn the majority of their revenues from silver mining.

SLVP holds a concentrated basket of silver mining companies in developed and emerging markets, but don't expect pure-play: its holdings just have to earn a majority of their revenues from silver mining, so you'll have exposure to companies that mine gold and precious metals, in addition to silver. The fund targets 25 companies and may extend its universe to micro- cap firms to reach this target. The index is market-cap-weighted and implements a capping methodology for diversification. It caps large and midcap gold companies to 5% then, it limits each issuer to 25% of the index, with issuers greater than 5% weight in aggregate capped at 50% of the index market capitalization. The index is reviewed quarterly starting each February.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the investment results of the MSCI ACWI Select Silver Miners Investable Market Index. The fund generally will invest at least 80% of its assets in the component securities of the underlying index and in investments that have economic characteristics that are substantially identical to the component securities of the underlying index. The index has been developed by MSCI Inc. (the "index provider" or "MSCI") to focus on approximately 25 companies in developed and emerging markets that are involved in silver mining or exploration. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This ETF seeks to track a market-cap-weighted index developed by MSCI, focusing on approximately 25 global companies in developed and emerging markets that are involved in silver mining or exploration. The index specifically targets companies that earn a majority of their revenue from silver mining, although the concentrated basket may include exposure to companies that also mine other precious metals. While market-cap-weighted, the index incorporates a capping methodology to limit concentration among its constituents and is reviewed quarterly. The fund generally invests at least 80% of its assets in the index's components or investments with substantially identical economic characteristics and is classified as non-diversified.

name: Global X Video Games & Esports ETF
description_original: The fund invests at least 80% of its total assets in the securities of the underlying index and in American Depositary Receipts ("ADRs") and Global Depositary Receipts ("GDRs") based on the securities in the underlying index. The underlying index is designed to provide exposure to exchange-listed companies that are positioned to benefit from increased consumption related to video games and esports. It is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
HERO tracks a modified market-cap-weighted global index of companies in video games and esports industry.

HERO provides access to companies whose principal business have or are expected have significant exposure to the field of video games and esports. An algorithm screens company filings for keywords that match the index theme to identify and rank companies. Eligible securities meeting minimum market-cap and liquidity requirements must also generate at least 50% of its revenues from video games or esports activities to be selected for index inclusion. Securities are those in the emerging and developed countries. The fund also invests in ADRs and GDRs based on such securities, and is not limited to any sector or geography constraints. The index is market-cap weighted with caps placed on individual positions to limit concentration in large-cap companies. The index is reconstituted and reweighted semi-annually.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to provide investment results that correspond generally to the price and yield performance, before fees and expenses, of the Solactive Video Games & Esports Index. The fund invests at least 80% of its total assets in the securities of the underlying index and in American Depositary Receipts ("ADRs") and Global Depositary Receipts ("GDRs") based on the securities in the underlying index. The underlying index is designed to provide exposure to exchange-listed companies that are positioned to benefit from increased consumption related to video games and esports. It is non-diversified.
merged_description: This ETF aims to provide investment exposure to exchange-listed companies globally that are engaged in the video games and esports industry and are positioned to benefit from increased consumption in this area. It seeks to track the performance of an underlying index by investing at least 80% of its total assets in the index securities, including related American and Global Depositary Receipts. The index identifies companies with significant exposure, typically requiring at least 50% of revenue from video games or esports activities, using keyword screening across developed and emerging markets. The index utilizes a modified market-cap weighting approach with caps on individual positions and is reconstituted and reweighted semi-annually. It is classified as non-diversified.

name: Direxion Daily Dow Jones Internet Bull 3X Shares
description_original: The fund, under normal circumstances, invests at least 80% of its net assets in financial instruments, such as swap agreements, securities of the index, and ETFs that track the index and other financial instruments that provide daily leveraged exposure to the index or to ETFs that track the index. The index includes companies that generate at least 50% of their annual sales/revenue from the internet as determined by the index provider. It is non-diversified. It is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
WEBL provides 3x leveraged daily exposure to a market-cap-weighted index of the largest and most liquid U.S. Internet companies.

WEBL is passively managed to provide 3x leveraged daily exposure to the Dow Jones Internet Composite Index. The index is composed of the 40 largest and most actively traded U.S. internet technology and commerce companies. Companies selected are determined by the Index Provider to derive a majority of their sales from activities such as online retail, social media, advertising, travel platforms, cloud computing or digital marketing. Because of daily rebalancing and the compounding over time, the return of the Fund for periods longer than a day, will very likely differ from 300% of the return of the Index over the same period.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks daily investment results, before fees and expenses, of 300% of the daily performance of the Dow Jones Internet Composite Index. The fund, under normal circumstances, invests at least 80% of its net assets in financial instruments, such as swap agreements, securities of the index, and ETFs that track the index, that, in combination, provide 3X daily leveraged exposure to the index, consistent with the fund's investment objective. The index includes companies that generate at least 50% of their annual sales/revenue from the internet as determined by the index provider. It is non-diversified.
merged_description: This fund is designed to provide 300% (3x) leveraged daily investment results, before fees and expenses, corresponding to the daily performance of the Dow Jones Internet Composite Index. It is passively managed and, under normal circumstances, invests at least 80% of its net assets in financial instruments, such as swap agreements, securities of the index, and ETFs that track the index, to achieve this leveraged exposure. The underlying index is market-cap-weighted and composed of the largest and most liquid U.S. internet technology and commerce companies that generate at least 50% of their annual sales or revenue from internet-related activities, including online retail, social media, advertising, travel platforms, cloud computing, and digital marketing. The fund is non-diversified, and due to its daily rebalancing strategy and compounding over time, returns for periods longer than a single day will very likely differ significantly from 300% of the index return for the same period.

name: SPDR S&P Emerging Markets Dividend ETF
description_original: The SPDR S&P Emerging Markets Dividend ETF seeks to provide investment results that, before fees and expenses, correspond generally to the total return performance of the S&P Emerging Markets Dividend Opportunities Index (the “Index”)Seeks to provide exposure to the 100 emerging market stocks with highest risk-adjusted yield that have passed stability and dividend growth screensThe index is weighted based on trailing 12-month dividend yield. For potential diversification, no single country or GICS sector weight can be greater than 25%, and no stock weight can be greater than 3% in the Index
description_eftcom: EDIV departs significantly from market-like coverage as it pursues dividends in emerging markets. The fund seeks to deliver a portfolio of 100 high-yielding common stocks by ranking securities based on risk-adjusted yield, and screening for positive earnings-per-share and stable 3-year dividend growth. Stocks are then weighted by their 12-month dividend yield, subject to single security and country/sector weight caps of 3% and 25%, respectively. EDIV shows a bias toward mid and small-caps rather than a more market-like bulge toward larger firms. The fund also comes with country and sector bets, with financials and energy companies taking a back seat in favor of tech and utilities. The index is reconstituted annually and rebalanced semi-annually.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks investment results that, before fees and expenses, correspond generally to the total return performance of the S&P Emerging Markets Dividend Opportunities Index. The fund generally invests substantially all, but at least 80%, of its total assets in the securities comprising the index and in depositary receipts based on securities comprising the index. The index is designed to measure the performance of 100 high-yielding emerging market common stocks.
merged_description: This ETF seeks to track the performance of an index focusing on 100 high-yielding common stocks in emerging markets. It selects securities based on risk-adjusted yield, screening for stability, positive earnings, and stable dividend growth. Holdings are weighted by their trailing 12-month dividend yield, with constraints limiting any single stock to 3% and any country or sector to 25% for diversification. This approach can result in a portfolio emphasizing mid and small-cap companies and potentially creating country or sector concentrations compared to market-cap-weighted funds. The underlying index is reconstituted annually and rebalanced semi-annually.

name: Strategy Shares Newfound/ReSolve Robust Momentum ETF
description_original: The fund employs a "passive management" investment approach designed to track the total return performance, before fees and expenses, of the Newfound/ReSolve Robust Equity Momentum Index. The index uses a quantitative, rules-based methodology to provide exposure to broad U.S. equity, international equity, and emerging market equity indices, to the extent that such equity indices are exhibiting positive momentum relative to U.S. Treasury market indices.
description_eftcom:
ROMO is a passively managed fund-of-funds that shifts exposure to global equities regionally or U.S. Treasurys based on momentum and trend.

ROMO tracks an index that uses a quantitative, rules-based methodology to tilt exposure to global equities or U.S. Treasury based on momentum and multiple trend-following signals. The index can include one to five ETFs that represent U.S., developed and emerging market equities as well as short- and intermediate-term U.S. Treasury bonds. The ETFs exhibiting the strongest momentum and positive trend-following characteristics relative to Treasury securities are allocated more weight. ROMO may hold 100% exposure to developed market equity ETFs, while emerging market exposure is capped at 25%. The fund could shift 100% exposure to Treasury ETFs when the momentum and trend factors for the equity ETFs are negative relative to the U.S. Treasury market. The index is rebalanced every week and reconstituted annually in December.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to provide investment returns that correspond, before fees and expenses, to the performance of the Newfound/ReSolve Robust Equity Momentum Index. The fund employs a "passive management" investment approach designed to track the total return performance, before fees and expenses, of the Newfound/ReSolve Robust Equity Momentum Index. The index uses a quantitative, rules-based methodology to provide exposure to broad U.S. equity, international equity, and emerging market equity indices, to the extent that such equity indices are exhibiting positive momentum relative to U.S. Treasury market indices.
merged_description: This is a passively managed fund-of-funds designed to track a quantitative, rules-based index. The index employs a strategy that shifts exposure between global equity markets, including U.S., developed, and emerging regions, and U.S. Treasury bonds. This allocation is determined by evaluating momentum and trend-following signals, specifically assessing the relative strength of equities compared to U.S. Treasurys. The fund provides exposure to these equity asset classes when they exhibit positive momentum relative to Treasurys, potentially allocating up to 100% to developed market equities while capping emerging markets at 25%. Conversely, it can shift entirely to U.S. Treasury ETFs when equity momentum signals are negative relative to Treasurys. The underlying index is rebalanced weekly to adapt to changing market conditions.

name: Invesco S&P 500 Equal Weight Real Estate ETF
description_original: The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise the underlying index. The underlying index is composed of all of the components of the S&P 500® Real Estate Index, an index that contains the common stocks of all companies included in the S&P 500® Index that are classified as members of the real estate sector, as defined according to the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS).
description_eftcom: RSPR is the first equal-weighted ETF in the US real estate segment. Equal-weighting shrinks the footprint of the largest REITs in the portfolio, but the funds S&P 500 universe excludes small-caps, which would otherwise tilt the portfolio much smaller. The fund includes a small portion of non-REIT real estate management and development companies, while mortgage REITs are out of bounds. In all, RSPR offers a concentrated, equal-weight alternative in a space dominated by cap-weighted funds. Through September 2016, RSPR had failed to attract any investor interest. This changed somewhat due to an unusual arrangement with sister fund RSPF, which needed to divest itself of REITs to comply with a GICS classification change. RSPF provided AUM in the form of REITs to RSPR in return for its shares, which were then distributed to RSPF shareholders as of Sep. 16, 2016, thus providing a modest but critical boost to RSPRs AUM. Prior to June 7, 2023, the fund traded under the ticker EWRE.
merged_description: This ETF offers investors exposure to the U.S. Real Estate sector by tracking an index derived from the S&P 500 Real Estate Index. Distinctively, it employs an equal-weighting methodology across the common stocks of S&P 500 companies classified in the Real Estate sector according to GICS. The portfolio encompasses real estate management and development companies alongside REITs, while explicitly excluding mortgage REITs, providing a concentrated, equal-weight alternative in this market segment.

name: First Trust Utilities AlphaDEX Fund
description_original: The fund will normally invest at least 90% of its net assets (including investment borrowings) in the common stocks that comprise the index. The index is a modified equal-dollar weighted index to objectively identify and select stocks from the Russell 1000® Index in the utilities sector that may generate positive alpha relative to traditional passive-style indices through the use of the AlphaDEX® selection methodology.
description_eftcom:
FXU tracks a tiered, equal-weighted index of large- and mid-cap utility firms in the US. Holdings are selected and weighted based on growth and value metrics.

FXU uses a quant-based model to pick stocks that are predicted to outperform the broader US utilities market. In particular, the fund selects companies based on their value and growth factors, and then weights them equally in tiers. This process favors firms on the extreme ends of the style spectrum, and results to a portfolio that has a significant tilt toward mid-caps. FXU also includes a large allocation to telecom companies. Overall, the fund offers a smart beta approach to the US utilities space, instead of providing market-like sector exposure. The index is reconstituted and rebalanced quarterly.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks investment results that correspond generally to the price and yield (before the fund's fees and expenses) of an equity index called the StrataQuant® Utilities Index. The fund will normally invest at least 90% of its net assets (including investment borrowings) in the securities that comprise the index. The index is a modified equal-dollar weighted index to objectively identify and select stocks from the Russell 1000® Index in the utilities sector that may generate positive alpha relative to traditional passive-style indices through the use of the AlphaDEX® selection methodology.
merged_description: This ETF employs a smart beta strategy focused on the U.S. utilities sector, drawing its constituents from the Russell 1000 Index. Utilizing a quantitative model known as AlphaDEX®, it selects stocks based on growth and value factors with the aim of generating positive alpha relative to traditional passive benchmarks. The index applies a modified equal-dollar weighting, structuring the portfolio with stocks weighted equally within tiers. This methodology leads to a unique composition, including a significant tilt towards mid-capitalization firms and a notable allocation to telecom companies, distinguishing it from standard market-cap weighted utilities funds. The fund normally invests at least 90% of its assets in the securities comprising the index, which is reconstituted and rebalanced quarterly.

name: John Hancock Multifactor Media and Communications ETF
description_original: The fund normally invests at least 80% of its net assets (plus any borrowings for investment purposes) in securities that compose the fund's index. The index is designed to comprise securities in the media and communications sector within the U.S. Universe whose market capitalizations are larger than that of the 1001st largest U.S. company at the time of reconstitution. It is non-diversified.
merged_description: This ETF aims to track an index composed of companies within the U.S. media and communications sector, focusing on those with market capitalizations larger than the 1001st largest U.S. company at the time of index reconstitution. The fund typically invests at least 80% of its net assets in the securities that make up this index. It is categorized as a non-diversified fund.

name: Xtrackers J.P. Morgan ESG USD High Yield Corporate Bond ETF
description_original: The fund will invest at least 80% of its total assets, but typically far more, in instruments that comprise the underlying index. The index generally aims to keep the broad characteristics of its parent index, the J.P. Morgan DM High Yield USD Index (a USD denominated high yield corporate bond index of developed market issuers), resulting in a broad high yield fixed income market exposure with ESG aspects.
description_eftcom: The security is being delisted. The last day of trading on an exchange is March 13, 2024. ESHY starts with the J.P. Morgan DM High Yield USD Index and screens for ESG considerations. The index provider uses third party research to determine an ESG valuation for each issuer, which is translated into a score ranging from 0-100 and assigns them to a quintile depending on their score. The lowest quintile as well as those involved in thermal coal, tobacco, weapons, or UN principle violation are removed from the selection. Remaining securities are then weighted based their quintile, with the best scorers being over-weighted. Bonds categorized as having green and climate friendly assets or projects are upgraded one quintile from its original assignment. The index is rebalanced monthly. Prior to May 12, 2020, the fund name was Xtrackers High Yield Corporate Bond - Interest Rate Hedged ETF under ticker: HYIH, and tracked Solactive High Yield Corporate Bond - Interest Rate Hedged Index.
merged_description: This ETF provides broad exposure to USD-denominated high yield corporate bonds from developed markets by tracking an index based on the J.P. Morgan DM High Yield USD Index, with significant ESG integration. The index employs third-party research to evaluate issuers for ESG considerations, excluding those with the lowest scores and companies involved in specific controversial activities like thermal coal or tobacco. Securities are then weighted based on their ESG evaluation, favoring higher scores, and bonds with green or climate-friendly characteristics receive a positive adjustment. The underlying index is rebalanced monthly. It is important to note that this security is being delisted, with the final day of trading on an exchange scheduled for March 13, 2024.

name: Invesco DWA Consumer Cyclicals Momentum ETF
description_original: The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise the underlying index. The underlying index is composed of at least 30 securities of companies in the consumer discretionary (or cyclicals) sector that have powerful relative strength or "momentum" characteristics.
description_eftcom:
PEZ tracks an index of US consumer cyclical firms selected and weighted by price momentum.

PEZ follows a Dorsey-Wright relative strength index that selects and weights US consumer cyclical stocks by price momentum. Index construction begins by assigning a momentum score to the 2,000 largest constituents by market cap in the NASDAQ US Benchmark index. The score is based on upward price movements of the security compared to the benchmark and other eligible securities within the universe. The top 30 highest momentum-scoring stocks in the consumer discretionary sector are then chosen for the index with higher scoring securities receiving greater weight. The portfolio tilts small, with a growth bias and somewhat higher risk. The index is reconstituted and rebalanced quarterly. Prior to August 28, 2023, the fund traded under the name Invesco DWA Consumer Cyclicals Momentum ETF.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the investment results (before fees and expenses) of the Dorsey Wright® Consumer Cyclicals Technical Leaders Index (the "underlying index"). The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise the underlying index. The underlying index is composed of at least 30 securities of companies in the consumer discretionary (or cyclicals) sector that have powerful relative strength or "momentum" characteristics.
merged_description: This ETF aims to track the investment results of a momentum-weighted index focused on the U.S. consumer discretionary sector. The underlying Dorsey Wright® index identifies companies exhibiting strong relative price momentum characteristics within the consumer cyclicals sector, typically selecting at least 30 securities. Higher-momentum stocks receive greater weight in the index. The fund generally invests at least 90% of its assets in these index securities, which are reconstituted and rebalanced quarterly. The resulting portfolio may exhibit a tilt towards smaller companies with a growth bias and potentially carry somewhat higher risk.

name: The Materials Select Sector SPDR Fund
description_original: The Materials Select Sector SPDR Fund seeks to provide investment results that, before expenses, correspond generally to the price and yield performance of the Materials Select Sector Index (the “Index”).The Index seeks to provide an effective representation of the materials sector of the S&P 500 Index.Seeks to provide precise exposure to companies in the chemical; metals and mining; paper and forest products; containers and packaging; and construction material industries.Allows investors to take strategic or tactical positions at a more targeted level than traditional style based investing.
description_eftcom:
XLB tracks a market-cap-weighted index of US basic materials companies. The fund includes only the materials components of the S&P 500.

XLB invests in basic materials companies from the S&P 500, these would include companies in the chemicals, metals and mining, paper and forest products, containers and packaging, and construction materials industry. Its limited selection universe means it is heavily concentrated, and individual holdings must be taken into consideration before investing in this fund. Not surprisingly, XLB favors large-caps. Components of the index are all picked by the index committee, and weighed by free-float market capitalization, subject to a cap to ensure diversification requirements. Index rebalancing occurs quarterly.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to provide investment results that, before expenses, correspond generally to the price and yield performance of publicly traded equity securities of companies in the Materials Select Sector Index. In seeking to track the performance of the index, the fund employs a replication strategy. It generally invests substantially all, but at least 95%, of its total assets in the securities comprising the index. The index includes securities of companies from the following industries: chemicals; metals and mining; paper and forest products; containers and packaging; and construction materials. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This fund tracks an index that represents the materials sector of the S&P 500 Index, aiming to provide investment results corresponding generally to the price and yield performance of publicly traded equity securities within this sector. It invests primarily in companies from specific industries including chemicals; metals and mining; paper and forest products; containers and packaging; and construction materials. It employs a replication strategy, investing substantially all its assets in the index constituents. The index is market-cap weighted, adjusted for free-float and subject to diversification caps, and is rebalanced quarterly. Due to its focused scope on a limited selection universe, the fund is considered non-diversified and concentrated, typically favoring large-cap stocks, offering investors targeted exposure to this sector.

name: ALPS O'Shares Europe Quality Dividend ETF Shares
description_original: The underlying index is designed to measure the performance of publicly-listed large-capitalization and mid-capitalization dividend-paying issuers in Europe that meet certain market capitalization, liquidity, high quality, low volatility and dividend yield thresholds, as determined by O'Shares Investment Advisers, LLC (the "index provider"). Under normal market conditions, the fund will invest at least 80% of its total assets in the components of the underlying index.
description_eftcom: OEUR, along with the US-focused OUSA, was part of the first launch from OShares Investments. The fund brings a factor-based, high-dividend-yield approach to large-cap-European equities. Stocks are selected from an index of roughly 500 of the largest publicly listed firms within Developed Europe that are weighted by three factors: high quality, low volatility, and high dividend yield. Multiple metrics within each factor are averaged to develop an overall ranking score. Securities are weighted based on a score-modified market-cap, then selecting the top 50 highest-weighted companies. The fund places caps of 5% on any one constituent at each quarterly rebalance and a sector weight cap of 22% during semi-annual reconstitution. Before June 1, 2020, OEUR was named O'Shares FTSE Europe Quality Dividend ETF and tracked FTSE Developed Europe Qual/Vol/Yield 5% Capped Factor Index. On June 17, 2022, ALPS became the fund advisor, adding the reference to the fund name.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the performance (before fees and expenses) of the O'Shares Europe Quality Dividend Index (the "underlying index"). The underlying index is designed to measure the performance of publicly-listed large-capitalization and mid-capitalization dividend-paying issuers in Europe that meet certain market capitalization, liquidity, high quality, low volatility and dividend yield thresholds, as determined by O'Shares Investment Advisers, LLC (the "index provider"). Under normal market conditions, the fund will invest at least 80% of its total assets in the components of the underlying index.
merged_description: This ETF seeks to track a factor-based index designed to measure the performance of publicly-listed large and mid-capitalization, dividend-paying issuers in Developed Europe. The index selects companies meeting certain market capitalization, liquidity, high quality, low volatility, and high dividend yield thresholds. Securities are weighted based on a score-modified market-cap derived from these factor metrics, typically resulting in a portfolio of approximately 50 holdings. To manage concentration, the index includes constraints such as a 5% cap on any single constituent at quarterly rebalances and a 22% cap on sectors semi-annually. Under normal market conditions, the fund invests at least 80% of its total assets in the components of this index, providing investors with exposure to a focused approach on quality, low volatility, and high dividend yield within the European equity market.

name: First Trust US Equity Opportunities UCITS ETF
description_original: The fund will normally invest at least 90% of its net assets (including investment borrowings) in the common stocks that comprise the index. The index seeks to measure the performance of equity securities of the 100 typically largest and most liquid initial public offerings ("IPOs") (including spin-offs and equity carve-outs) of U.S. companies. It is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
FPX tracks a market-cap-weighted index of the 100 largest US IPOs over the first 1,000 trading days for each stock.

FPX holds positions in the 100 largest, and typically most liquid, US firms with recent IPOs. Eligible stocks are purchased after the close on the 6th trading day and sold on the 1000th, for a holding period of roughly 4 years. The fund applies further quantitative screens in addition to the usual de minimis size and liquidity requirements, but these are fairly relaxed. It is also market cap-weighted with a capping scheme of 10% for each individual security. See sibling funds FPXE and FPXI for Europe and broad international exposure, respectively, using the same methodology. Prior to December 14, 2016, the fund traded with the name First Trust US IPO Index ETF, however its name change bore no impact to FPXs investment strategy. One caveat worth noting: In the case of an index constituent merging with or being acquired by a mature company, the resulting entity will remain included in the index.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks investment results that correspond generally to the price and yield (before the fund's fees and expenses) of an equity index called the IPOX®-100 U.S. Index. The fund will normally invest at least 90% of its net assets (including investment borrowings) in the securities that comprise the index. The index seeks to measure the performance of equity securities of the 100 typically largest and most liquid initial public offerings ("IPOs") (including spin-offs and equity carve-outs) of U.S. companies. It is non-diversified.
merged_description: This ETF seeks investment results that generally correspond to the performance of a specific equity index focused on initial public offerings (IPOs). The index measures the performance of equity securities from the 100 typically largest and most liquid U.S. IPOs, which can include spin-offs and equity carve-outs. The fund normally invests at least 90% of its net assets in the common stocks comprising this index. The underlying index is market-cap-weighted with a 10% cap per security. Eligible stocks, typically among the largest and most liquid U.S. firms with recent IPOs, are included after the 6th trading day and remain in the index for approximately 1,000 trading days, which is about four years. Quantitative screens are also applied for selection. A distinctive feature is that a constituent remains in the index even if it merges with or is acquired by a mature company. The fund is considered non-diversified.

name: VanEck Social Sentiment ETF
description_original: The fund normally invests at least 80% of its total assets in securities that comprise the fund's benchmark index. The index is comprised of common stocks of U.S. companies selected by a rules-based quantitative methodology developed by the index Provider, which is designed to identify the U.S. common stocks with the most "positive insights" collected from online sources including social media, news articles, blog posts and other alternative datasets. The fund is non-diversified.
description_eftcom: BUZZ seeks to reflect the investor sentiment online. It looks for investment-related mentions of large- and midcap US-listed firms in relevant online sources including social media, news articles and blog posts. Using a proprietary algorithm, eligible companies that meet certain market-cap and liquidity requirements are scored and ranked by insight, which indicates the degree of positive sentiment and breadth of discussion on the internet. Based on this scoring process, BUZZ curates a concentrated portfolio of 75 firms with the most positive investor sentiment. Holdings are weighted using a proprietary scoring model, with single constituent weights capped at 3%. The index is reconstituted and rebalanced monthly.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track as closely as possible, before fees and expenses, the price and yield performance of the BUZZ NextGen AI US Sentiment Leaders Index. The fund normally invests at least 80% of its total assets in securities that comprise the fund's benchmark index. The index is comprised of common stocks of U.S. companies selected by a rules-based quantitative methodology developed by the index Provider, which is designed to identify the U.S. common stocks with the most "positive insights" collected from online sources including social media, news articles, blog posts and other alternative datasets. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This ETF seeks to reflect online investor sentiment by tracking an index comprised of U.S. common stocks. The index utilizes a rules-based quantitative methodology to identify stocks exhibiting the most positive insights gathered from various online sources, including social media, news articles, blog posts, and other alternative datasets. The fund normally invests at least 80% of its assets in the securities of this index, resulting in a concentrated portfolio of approximately 75 holdings. These holdings are weighted using a proprietary model with individual constituents capped at 3%, and the index is reconstituted and rebalanced monthly. The fund is considered non-diversified.

name: John Hancock Multifactor Energy ETF
description_original: The fund normally invests at least 80% of its net assets (plus any borrowings for investment purposes) in securities that compose the fund's index. The index is designed to comprise securities in the energy sector within the U.S. Universe whose market capitalizations are larger than that of the 1001st largest U.S. company at the time of reconstitution. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This fund aims to track an index focused on the U.S. energy sector, specifically including securities with market capitalizations larger than the 1001st largest U.S. company at the time of reconstitution. The fund normally invests at least 80% of its net assets in the securities that compose this index and is classified as non-diversified.

name: Pacer Industrials and Logistics ETF
description_original: A rules-based exchange traded fund (ETF) that aims to offer investors exposure to globally-listed stocks and depositary receipts involved in the support and functioning of global distribution supply chains.
description_eftcom: SHPP is passively managed to invest in globally listed stocks and depositary receipts of industrials and logistics companies. The fund includes firms that derive at least 50% of their revenue from: (i) transportation, such as air, ocean, and rail freight, trucking, and other courier services, (ii) software, including transportation management services and logistics software, (iii) hardware, such as robotics and forklifts, or (iv) consultation services that support global supply chains. The selection process starts with companies that meet size and liquidity criteria. Eligible firms are then screened based on descriptions of a companys business activities in regulatory filings, analyst reports, website, and industry-specific trade publications. Holdings are weighted by market-cap, subject to a 10% single security capping. In addition, the aggregate weight of constituents with over 4.5% allocation is capped at 45%. The index reconstitutes and rebalances annually.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the total return performance, before fees and expenses, of the Pacer Global Supply Chain Infrastructure Index. The fund employs a “passive management” (or indexing) investment approach designed to track the total return performance, before fees and expenses, of the index. The index consists of globally-listed stocks and depositary receipts of industrials and logistics companies. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This is a passively managed, rules-based exchange traded fund designed to provide exposure to companies supporting global distribution supply chains by tracking a specific index. The fund invests in globally listed stocks and depositary receipts primarily within the industrials and logistics sectors. Its strategy focuses on firms deriving over 50% of revenue from essential supply chain activities such as transportation, logistics software, hardware (like robotics), and related consultation services. Company selection involves screens for size, liquidity, and business focus, with holdings weighted by market capitalization subject to concentration limits. The fund is non-diversified and its underlying index is reconstituted and rebalanced annually.

name: SPDR MSCI USA Climate Paris Aligned ETF
description_original: NZUS seeks to provide investment results that, before fees and expenses, correspond generally to the MSCI USA Climate Paris Aligned Index (“the Index”)Seeks to track an index designed to reduce exposure to the physical and transition risks of climate change and increase target exposure to sustainable investment opportunities by incorporating the recommendations of the Taskforce on Climate Related Financial Disclosures (TCFD) and minimum requirements of the EU Paris Aligned BenchmarkMay be considered by investors seeking to implement net-zero strategies and address climate change in a holistic way
description_eftcom:
NZUS tracks a tier-weighted index of large- and mid-cap US stocks selected and weighted based on ESG criteria that are compatible with the Paris Climate Agreement and carbon reduction goals.

NZUS takes a climate approach to investing in the US large- and mid-cap space by tracking an index geared toward a low-carbon economy transition. The index initially screens out stocks from the MSCI USA Index, that are involved in controversial weapons, tobacco, thermal coal mining, oil and gas, and power generation, as well as severe ESG controversies and environmental issues. The portfolio selection and weighting utilize an optimization process that minimizes exposure to physical and transition risks of climate change while providing exposure to sustainable investment opportunities. Optimization constraints include greenhouse gas intensity reduction, low carbon transition score, climate value-at-risk, green revenue, and fossil fuels-based revenue. The index also uses an optimizer to maintain the sector weighting in the parent index. NZUS uses a sampling strategy to track its index, which is rebalanced semi-annually.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to provide investment results that, before fees and expenses, correspond generally to the total return performance of the MSCI USA Climate Paris Aligned Index. The fund generally invests substantially all, but at least 80%, of its total assets in the securities comprising the index. The index is designed to exceed the minimum standards for a “Paris-Aligned Benchmark” under the EU BMR. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This investment seeks to mirror the performance of an index focused on US large and mid-cap stocks. The index is constructed to align with the goals of the Paris Climate Agreement and support a low-carbon economy transition by selecting and weighting companies based on specific climate and ESG criteria. It screens out companies involved in controversial weapons, tobacco, thermal coal, oil and gas, and certain power generation, as well as those with severe ESG controversies. An optimization process further reduces exposure to climate change risks, both physical and transition, and increases exposure to sustainable investment opportunities, using metrics such as greenhouse gas intensity, climate value-at-risk, and green revenue, while aiming to maintain sector weights similar to the broad US market. The index is designed to meet or exceed the minimum requirements for EU Paris-Aligned Benchmarks and may incorporate recommendations from the Taskforce on Climate Related Financial Disclosures (TCFD), potentially fitting into investors' net-zero strategies.

name: Defiance Nasdaq Junior Biotechnology ETF
description_original: The investment seeks to track the total return performance, before fees and expenses, of the NASDAQ Junior Biotechnology Index. The index is a rules-based index that consists of a portfolio of the stock of U.S.-listed small capitalization ("junior") companies screened from the universe of the NASDAQ Biotechnology Index. The fund will generally use a "replication" strategy to achieve its investment objective, meaning it will generally invest in all of the component securities of the index in the same approximate proportions as in the index. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This ETF aims to mirror the total return of an index focused on U.S.-listed small-capitalization companies within the biotechnology sector, which are selected using specific rules from a broader biotechnology universe. It generally aims to achieve this by investing in the same securities as the underlying index in similar proportions. The fund is classified as non-diversified.

name: Direxion Daily Semiconductor Bull 3X Shares
description_original: The fund invests at least 80% of its net assets (plus borrowing for investment purposes) in financial instruments, such as swap agreements, securities of the index, and ETFs that track the index and other financial instruments that provide daily leveraged exposure to the index or to ETFs that track the index. The index is a rules-based, modified float-adjusted market capitalization-weighted index that tracks the performance of the thirty largest U.S. listed semiconductor companies. The fund is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
SOXL provides 3x daily exposure to a modified market-cap-weighted index of 30 US-listed semiconductor companies.

SOXL is an aggressive and bullish 1-day bet on a concentrated portfolio of the 30 largest US-listed semiconductor companies, including manufacturers and providers of services or equipment associated with semiconductors. The funds index employs market-cap-weighting, with the weights of the top five securities capped at 8% and the remaining securities at 4%. The index may include ADRs, whose cumulative weight is capped at 10%. To gain exposure to the index, the fund invests in swap agreements, securities of the index, and ETFs that track the index. SOXL rebalances its 3x leverage dailymeaning over the long haul, targeted returns could look significantly different due to compounding effects of this daily rebalance. Prior to August 25, 2021, the fund tracked the PHLX Semiconductor Sector Index.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks daily investment results, before fees and expenses, of 300% of the daily performance of the ICE Semiconductor Index. The fund invests at least 80% of its net assets in financial instruments, such as swap agreements, securities of the index, and ETFs that track the index, that, in combination, provide 3X daily leveraged exposure to the index, consistent with the fund's investment objective. The index is a rules-based, modified float-adjusted market capitalization-weighted index that tracks the performance of the thirty largest U.S. listed semiconductor companies. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This ETF aims to achieve daily investment results corresponding to 300% of the daily performance of the ICE Semiconductor Index, before fees and expenses. The fund gains exposure by investing at least 80% of its net assets in financial instruments such as swap agreements, securities of the index, and ETFs tracking the index, along with other instruments providing daily leveraged exposure. The underlying index is a rules-based, modified float-adjusted market capitalization-weighted index tracking the thirty largest U.S. listed semiconductor companies, including manufacturers, service providers, and equipment companies, and applies specific weight limitations to its constituents. Due to its daily leverage and rebalancing strategy, this non-diversified fund is intended for short-term, typically daily, use, and its performance over periods longer than one day may diverge significantly from three times the index's return because of compounding effects.

name: iShares MSCI Global Energy Producers ETF
description_original: The fund generally will invest at least 80% of its assets in the component securities of the underlying index and in investments that have economic characteristics that are substantially identical to the component securities of the underlying index. The index measures the combined performance of equity securities of companies in both developed and emerging markets that are primarily engaged in the business of energy exploration and production. The fund is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
FILL tracks an index of companies in developed and emerging markets that are primarily engaged in the business of energy exploration and production.

FILL offers exposure to the global Oil & Gas Exploration and Production (E&P) segment. It will invest in atleast 40% of its assets in issuers and businesses in developed and emerging markets. The fund covers the all cap exposure of its parent index MSCI ACWI Investable Market Index, then selects firms primarily engaged in the exploration and production of oil and gas or in the production and mining of coal and other consumable fuels related to the generation of energy as classified by GICS. It excludes firms whose majority of revenues are on downstream and alternative fuels business. However, FILL is not pure-play on Oil and Gas E&P space as it invests heavily into the Integrated Oil & Gas sector with companies like Exxon Mobil, BP and Chevron. Index constituents are reviewed quarterly.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the investment results of the MSCI ACWI Select Energy Producers Investable Market Index (IMI). The fund generally will invest at least 80% of its assets in the component securities of the underlying index and in investments that have economic characteristics that are substantially identical to the component securities of the underlying index. The index measures the combined performance of equity securities of companies in both developed and emerging markets that are primarily engaged in the business of energy exploration and production. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This ETF tracks an index of companies in developed and emerging markets that are primarily engaged in energy exploration and production. Specifically, this includes firms involved in the E&P of oil and gas, as well as the production and mining of coal and other consumable fuels. It aims for all-cap exposure and excludes companies with a majority of revenues from downstream or alternative fuels. The fund is non-diversified and generally invests at least 80% of its assets in the component securities of the underlying index or investments with substantially identical economic characteristics. While primarily focused on exploration and production, the fund is not a pure-play E&P investment as it includes integrated oil and gas companies. The underlying index constituents are reviewed quarterly.

name: Invesco S&P 500 Equal Weight Financials ETF
description_original: The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise the underlying index. The underlying index is composed of all of the components of the S&P 500® Financials Index, an index that contains the common stocks of all companies included in the S&P 500® Index that are classified as members of the financials sector, as defined according to the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS).
description_eftcom: RSPF offers an equal-weight play on the US financials sector. In contrast to market-cap-weighting, the funds equal-weighting scheme increases the impact of smaller firms in the portfolio at the expense of larger ones, and greatly reduces concentration to top holdings. For RSPF, this smaller-cap tilt is lessened by the fund's S&P 500-restricted universe, which excludes most small-caps. Still, its equal-weighting limits the importance of dominant players in the sector and creates more exposure to less known companies. This can become an advantage when markets are hostile toward big banks. The index is rebalanced on a quarterly basis. Prior to June 07, 2023, the fund traded under the ticker, RYF.
merged_description: This fund provides an equal-weighted investment approach to the US financials sector, primarily tracking an underlying index composed of all companies within the S&P 500 Index classified as members of the financials sector according to GICS. The strategy involves investing at least 90% of total assets in the securities of this index. By employing an equal-weighting scheme, the portfolio increases the impact of smaller firms within the S&P 500 financials universe and significantly reduces concentration towards larger, dominant companies compared to a market-cap-weighted methodology. The underlying index is rebalanced quarterly.

name: Putnam ESG Ultra Short ETF
description_original: The fund invests in a diversified short duration portfolio of fixed-income securities comprised of investment-grade money market and other fixed-income securities, including U.S. dollar-denominated foreign securities of these types, with a focus on companies or issuers that Putnam Management, the fund’s investment manager, believes meet relevant environmental, social or governance (“ESG”) criteria on a sector-specific basis (“ESG criteria”).
description_eftcom: PULT invests in short-term, investment grade fixed income securities from around the world that meet ESG standards on a sector-specific basis. The fund maintains a portfolio duration of no more than one year and a maturity of four years or less. It may include government and corporate debt securities. The fund assesses fundamentals that include the industry, location, strategic position, and key relationships. Securities are assigned an ESG rating, and only the highest-rated ones are considered. To identify relevant ESG criteria on a sector-specific basis, the fund uses an internally developed materiality map that determines which criteria are deemed important for a given sector. For example, securitized debt securities are broadly evaluated due to various asset types, counterparties, complex market structures, and scarce ESG data. Sovereign debt is evaluated using quantitative models and research, as better ESG scores may influence a countrys credit risk and borrowing costs.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks as high a rate of current income as Franklin Advisers, Inc. (Franklin Advisers) believes is consistent with preservation of capital and maintenance of liquidity. The fund invests in a diversified short duration portfolio of fixed-income securities comprised of investment-grade money market and other fixed-income securities, including U.S. dollar-denominated foreign securities of these types, with a focus on companies or issuers that Putnam Management, the fund’s investment manager, believes meet relevant environmental, social or governance (“ESG”) criteria on a sector-specific basis (“ESG criteria”).
merged_description: The investment strategy seeks high current income consistent with capital preservation and maintenance of liquidity by investing in a diversified portfolio of investment-grade, short-duration fixed-income securities. The portfolio includes money market instruments, government and corporate debt, and U.S. dollar-denominated foreign securities. A key focus is on issuers meeting relevant environmental, social, and governance (ESG) criteria, assessed on a sector-specific basis using an internally developed materiality map to identify crucial factors. Only the highest ESG-rated securities that also meet fundamental analysis are considered. The fund maintains a portfolio duration of no more than one year and a maturity of four years or less.

name: Amplify Natural Resources Dividend Income ETF
description_original: The fund will normally invest at least 80% of its net assets (plus borrowings for investment purposes) in the securities that comprise the index, which primarily include common stocks and/or depositary receipts. It will not concentrate its investments (i.e., invest more than 25% of the value of its total assets) in securities of issuers in any one industry or group of industries, except to the extent that the index concentrates in an industry or group of industries. The fund is non-diversified.
description_eftcom: NDIV offers a dividend-skewed take on the natural resources industry. Starting with a broad universe of dividend-paying US-listed equities and ADRs, the index screens for companies that: 1) derive more than 50% of their revenues in one of the following natural resource, commodity-related industries: energy (oil, gas & consumable fuels), chemicals, agriculture, precious and industrial metals and mining, paper products, and timber, 2) have a market-cap of at least $5 billion, 3) have an average daily traded value of at least $2 million over the last six months, and 4) have an indicated dividend yield of at least 3% annually. The index excludes companies domiciled in Russia. All securities that meet the eligibility screens are selected for inclusion and are weighted according to their indicated dividend yield. Single security weights are capped at 5%. The fund typically holds a narrow portfolio of 40 to 60 securities. The index reconstitutes and rebalances quarterly.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks investment results that generally correspond to the price and yield of the EQM Natural Resources Dividend Income Index. The fund will normally invest at least 80% of its net assets in the securities that comprise the index, which primarily include common stocks and/or depositary receipts. The index is a gross total return index that seeks to provide investment exposure to dividend-paying equity securities of global companies operating primarily in the following natural resource, commodity-related industries: energy; chemicals; agriculture; precious and industrial metals & mining; paper products; and timber. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This ETF seeks investment results that correspond to the price and yield of an index focusing on dividend-paying global companies primarily operating in natural resource and commodity-related industries, including energy, chemicals, agriculture, precious and industrial metals and mining, paper products, and timber. The fund typically invests at least 80% of its net assets in the securities comprising this index, which are primarily US-listed equities and depositary receipts. The underlying index employs specific screening criteria, requiring companies to derive over 50% of their revenue from these sectors, meet minimum thresholds for market capitalization ($5 billion), average daily traded value ($2 million), and annual dividend yield (3%), while excluding companies domiciled in Russia. Eligible securities are weighted based on their indicated dividend yield, with a 5% single security cap, resulting in a portfolio often holding a concentrated number of 40 to 60 securities. The index is reconstituted and rebalanced quarterly. The fund is classified as non-diversified.

name: MicroSectors U.S. Big Banks Index 3X Leveraged ETNs
description_original: The notes are senior unsecured medium-term notes issued by Bank of Montreal with a return linked to a three times leveraged participation in the performance of the index, compounded daily, less a Daily Investor Fee, the Daily Financing Charge and, if applicable, the Redemption Fee Amount. The index is an equal-dollar weighted index designed to represent the 10 U.S. stocks with the largest market capitalization in the banking sector.
description_eftcom:
BNKU tracks three times the performance of an equal-weighted index of US large banks.

BNKU is a leveraged take on US Big Banks. Specifically, the fund tracks three times the performance of the underlying index, which selects the 10 largest qualifying stocks and evenly weights them. Note, however, that the product isnt designed for long-term investors. The fund rebalances daily. As a result, compounding and path dependency make its long-term returns difficult to predict when compared to its underlying index. BNKU is essentially a relaunch of an old ETN that was available from April 2, 2019, to July 24, 2024, with the same ticker and exposure.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to provide three times leveraged participation in the gross total return version of the Solactive MicroSectors™ U.S. Big Banks Index. The ETNs are senior unsecured medium-term notes issued by Bank of Montreal with a return linked to a three times leveraged participation in the performance of the index, compounded daily, less a Daily Financing Charge, the Daily Investor Fee and, if applicable, the Redemption Fee Amount.
merged_description: This product is structured as senior unsecured notes issued by a bank, offering three times leveraged exposure to the performance of an equal-weighted index comprising the 10 largest U.S. stocks in the banking sector. The return is linked to three times the index performance, compounded daily, less applicable fees. Due to this daily compounding and rebalancing, the notes are typically not suitable for investors planning to hold them for periods longer than one day, as returns over longer periods can deviate significantly from three times the index's return.

name: Invesco S&P SmallCap Consumer Discretionary ETF
description_original: The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise the underlying index. These companies are principally engaged in the business of providing consumer goods and services that are cyclical in nature, including, but not limited to, household durables, leisure products and services, apparel and luxury goods, computers and electronics, automobiles and auto components, and hotel and restaurant services.
description_eftcom:
PSCD tracks a market-cap-weighted index of consumer discretionary firms selected from the S&P SmallCap 600.

PSCD represents the consumer cyclicals segment of the S&P SmallCap 600, a market-cap-weighted index that consists of US small-cap companies screened for size, liquidity, and financial viability. The fund uses GICS in identifying consumer discretionary firms, which may include those engaged in leisure products and services, apparel, luxury goods, automobiles, computers and electronics, and hotel and restaurant services. Selected securities are weighted by market cap and are constrained, such that individual securities will not exceed 22.5% weight and the aggregate weight of securities with over 4.5% allocation is capped at 45% weight of the portfolio. The index rebalances quarterly.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the investment results (before fees and expenses) of the S&P SmallCap 600® Capped Consumer Discretionary Index (the “underlying index”). The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise the underlying index. These companies are principally engaged in the business of providing consumer goods and services that are cyclical in nature, including, but not limited to, household durables, leisure products and services, apparel and luxury goods, computers and electronics, automobiles and auto components, and hotel and restaurant services.
merged_description: This fund seeks to track a market-cap-weighted index focused on the consumer discretionary sector within the S&P SmallCap 600. It invests primarily in US small-cap companies from this index, identified using GICS and screened for size, liquidity, and financial viability. These companies provide cyclical goods and services, such as household durables, leisure products and services, apparel and luxury goods, computers and electronics, automobiles and auto components, and hotel and restaurant services. The fund generally holds at least 90% of its assets in these securities, which are weighted by market cap but subject to capping constraints: individual holdings are capped at 22.5%, and the aggregate weight of securities exceeding 4.5% is capped at 45%. The underlying index rebalances quarterly.

name: Cabana Target Leading Sector Aggressive ETF
description_original: The fund is an actively managed ETF that seeks to achieve its investment objective primarily by allocating its assets among ETFs that invest in securities of companies in the various sectors of the U.S. market: communication services, consumer discretionary, consumer staples, energy, financials, health care, industrials, information technology, materials, real estate, and utilities. It is non-diversified.
description_eftcom: The security was delisted. The last day of trading on an exchange is January 05, 2024CLSA is an actively-managed fund-of-funds that allocate its exposure based on the economic conditions and market outlook for five very broad asset classes: equities, fixed income, real estate, currencies and commodities. Equities will include both domestic and foreign companies, including emerging markets. Fixed Income securities have no restrictions in terms of maturity, quality or duration. The Sub-Adviser uses a proprietary algorithm that combines fundamental economic and technical price data to identify investments in sectors that appear to be attractive based on the current business cycle. Through the algo, CLSA can also allocate across less-/non-correlated asset classes to manage volatility or any potential market declines. The fund utilizes an aggressive investment style, meaning it will aim for capital growth and maximize its returns. Note that the Sub-Adviser has full discretion to override the algo if a perceived breakdown or systemic change has occurred.
merged_description: This investment product was an actively managed fund-of-funds that was delisted, with its final trading day on January 5, 2024. Its strategy involved allocating exposure across five broad asset classes: equities (encompassing domestic and foreign, including emerging markets), fixed income (without restriction on maturity, quality, or duration), real estate, currencies, and commodities. A proprietary algorithm, which analyzed fundamental economic and technical price data in relation to the current business cycle, was used to identify attractive investments in various sectors. The algorithm also facilitated allocation across less or non-correlated asset classes for volatility management, reflecting the fund's aggressive investment style focused on capital growth, although the Sub-Adviser retained full discretion to override the algorithm; the fund was classified as non-diversified.

name: First Trust Dorsey Wright Focus 5 ETF
description_original: The fund will normally invest at least 90% of its net assets (including investment borrowings) in the exchange-traded funds ("ETFs") that comprise the index. The index is designed to provide targeted exposure to the five First Trust sector-based ETFs that the index provider believes offer the greatest potential to outperform the other ETFs in the selection universe and that satisfy certain trading volume and liquidity requirements.
description_eftcom: FV uses the Dorsey Wright relative strength model to make big bets on US sectors and global themes. The fund holds just 5 ETFsall from First Trustchosen from the issuer's entire stable of broad US sector funds and narrower global niche plays. The 5 ETFs are selected based on relative price momentum. The selected funds are then weighted equally in the portfolio. Note that while the underlying index measures relative strength weekly, an ETF won't drop out until it falls below the median level of relative strength in FV's small universe. This buffer is meant to reduce turnover. The underlying ETFs often use multi-factor exposure rather than cap-weighting, typically overweighting mid-caps. In short, FV looks nothing like a typical plain-vanilla global ETF. Still, the fund rounds out the picture of an accessible alternative exposure to global equities. The index is evaluated on a bi-monthly basis.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks investment results that correspond generally to the price and yield (before the fund's fees and expenses) of an index called the Dorsey Wright Focus Five Index (the "index"). The fund will normally invest at least 90% of its net assets (including investment borrowings) in the exchange-traded funds ("ETFs") that comprise the index. The index is designed to provide targeted exposure to the five First Trust sector-based ETFs that the index provider believes offer the greatest potential to outperform the other ETFs in the selection universe and that satisfy certain trading volume and liquidity requirements.
merged_description: This ETF seeks investment results corresponding to an index that identifies exchange-traded funds with strong relative price momentum. The fund normally invests at least 90% of its assets in the five equally-weighted ETFs comprising this index, which are selected from First Trust's universe of broad US sector and global niche funds. These five are chosen based on their potential to outperform, driven by relative strength analysis, and satisfying liquidity requirements. The underlying index is evaluated bi-monthly, with a buffer mechanism applied to reduce turnover. The chosen underlying ETFs often employ multi-factor strategies and typically overweight mid-caps, resulting in a portfolio that provides accessible alternative exposure to global equities and differs from standard plain-vanilla funds.

name: JPMorgan U.S. Tech Leaders ETF
description_original: The fund will invest primarily in equity securities issued by technology and technology-enabled companies which the adviser believes are leaders and where the magnitude and/or duration of future growth for these companies is underappreciated by the market.
description_eftcom: JTEK actively manages a portfolio of potential tech leaders from various industries. The adviser identifies US equities that exhibit disruptive business models, sustainable competitive advantages, large addressable markets, and a proven management team. The fund targets companies with underappreciated growth, assessed by analyzing company revenues, profit margins, and free cash flows against the consensus expectations over time. The fund focuses on the technology and communication services sectors and tech-enabled firms. Tech-enabled firms leverage new technologies to enhance their business. These may include electronics, engineering and construction, transportation, auto manufacturers, auto parts and equipment, entertainment, leisure time, retail, biotechnology, commercial services, healthcare services, pharmaceuticals, diversified financials, insurance, REITs, advertising, media, and energy-alternate sources. The adviser may integrate ESG factors into the selection process.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to provide long-term capital appreciation. The fund will invest primarily in equity securities issued by technology and technology-enabled companies which the adviser believes are leaders and where the magnitude and/or duration of future growth for these companies is underappreciated by the market.
merged_description: This actively managed ETF primarily seeks long-term capital appreciation by investing in equity securities of technology and technology-enabled companies. The adviser focuses on identifying potential leaders, particularly US equities, where the market is believed to underappreciate the magnitude or duration of future growth. These companies are assessed based on factors such as disruptive business models, sustainable competitive advantages, large addressable markets, and proven management teams, with growth potential evaluated by analyzing financials like revenues, profit margins, and free cash flows against consensus expectations. The focus extends beyond traditional tech to include tech-enabled firms across diverse industries, such as transportation, healthcare, retail, and financial services, that leverage new technologies. ESG factors may also be integrated into the selection process.

name: Breakwave Dry Bulk Shipping ETF
description_original: The fund seeks to achieve its investment objective by investing substantially all of its assets in the Freight Futures currently constituting the Benchmark Portfolio. The Benchmark Portfolio includes a combination of Capesize, Panamax and Supramax Freight Futures.
description_eftcom:
BDRY tracks an index of long-only exposure to the nearest calendar quarter of dry bulk freight futures contracts on specified indexes.

BDRY is the first ETP to provide exposure to freight futures. Dry bulk shipping is an instrumental part of the global commodity market, and uncorrelated with other major asset classes historically. Dry bulk carrier transport unpackaged dry cargo, such as iron ore, coal, and grain - distinct from tankers and containerized cargo ships. BDRY provides exposure to the charter rate for dry bulk shipping by holding near-dated freight futures contracts on three dry bulk indices. The portfolio uses a fixed weighting scheme, rebalanced annually, based on the cargo ships size category - Capesize freight futures contracts get 50% weight, Panamax contracts 40%, and Supramax contracts 10%. As futures are always an imperfect proxy for spot prices, and the freight futures market is often in contango, long-term holdings are subject to position decay.
