It aims to achieve its objective by primarily investing at least 80% of its net assets in common stocks of U.S. companies that pay dividends annually. The fund emphasizes companies with a strong track record of paying regular dividends, particularly quarterly, and those expected to increase dividends over the next one to five years. Portfolio selection focuses on 30 to 40 typically large-cap companies, evaluating them based on factors such as current dividend yield (often relative to the S&P 500 or with a clear path to higher yield), dividend stability, and dividend growth history and potential, utilizing analysis of balance sheets and metrics like ROE. Up to 15% of the fund's net assets may be invested in foreign securities.

name: iShares U.S. Energy ETF
description_original: The fund generally will invest at least 80% of its assets in the component securities of its underlying index and in investments that have economic characteristics that are substantially identical to the component securities of its underlying index. The underlying index measures the performance of the energy sector of the U.S. equity market. The fund is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
IYE tracks a market-cap-weighted index of large-cap US companies in the energy industry.

IYE covers the energy segment of the US large-cap equity market. The fund holds a concentrated portfolio of companies that facilitate production and distribution of oil and gas. The underlying index is part of Russells US large cap sector indicesa series of representative indices that integrates ICBs sector classification framework on Russell 1000. Holdings are market-cap-weighted, subject to regulatory capping which limits single security weights at 22.5% and aggregate weight of securities exceeding 4.5% allocation at 45%. Index rebalancing occurs quarterly. Prior to September 20, 2021, the fund tracked the Dow Jones U.S. Oil & Gas Index.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the investment results of the Russell 1000 Energy RIC 22.5/45 Capped Index composed of U.S. equities in the energy sector. The fund generally will invest at least 80% of its assets in the component securities of its underlying index and in investments that have economic characteristics that are substantially identical to the component securities of its underlying index. The underlying index measures the performance of the energy sector of the U.S. equity market. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This fund seeks to track a market-cap-weighted index focused on large-cap US companies within the energy sector. Covering the energy segment of the US large-cap equity market, the underlying index includes a concentrated portfolio of companies involved in oil and gas production and distribution. The index employs market-cap weighting, subject to regulatory caps that limit single securities to 22.5% and the aggregate of positions above 4.5% to 45%. As a non-diversified fund, it generally invests at least 80% of its assets in the component securities of this underlying index or investments with substantially identical economic characteristics.

name: Direxion S&P 500 High minus Low Quality ETF
description_original: The investment seeks investment results, before fees and expenses, that track the S&P 500Â® 150/50 Quality 0.30% Decrement Index. The fund, under normal circumstances, invests at least 80% of its net assets (plus borrowing for investment purposes) in securities that comprise the Long Component of the index or shares of exchange-traded funds ("ETFs") on the Long Component of the index. The index consists of a portfolio that has 150% long exposure to the S&P 500Â® Quality Index (the "Long Component") and 50% short (or inverse) exposure to the S&P 500Â® Quality - Lowest Quintile Index (the "Short Component"). It is non-diversified.
merged_description: This fund aims to track the performance of an index focused on quality within the S&P 500. The underlying index is designed to provide 150% long exposure to high-quality stocks and simultaneously 50% short (inverse) exposure to the lowest quality segment of the S&P 500. To achieve its objective, the fund normally invests at least 80% of its assets in securities or ETFs representing the long component of this index. The index's calculation includes a daily performance deduction of 0.30%. The fund is considered non-diversified.

name: Direxion Fallen Knives ETF
description_original: The fund, under normal circumstances, invests at least 80% of its assets in the securities that comprise the index or investments with economic characteristics similar to the securities included in the index. The index is designed by Indxx, LLC to consist of U.S. equity securities that have experienced considerable share price declines over the prior year but have financial health, suggesting that the security has potential for share price recovery in the future. It is non-diversified.
merged_description: This fund seeks exposure to U.S. equity securities identified by its underlying index, which focuses on companies that have experienced significant share price declines over the past year but maintain financial health suggesting potential for future recovery. Under normal circumstances, the fund invests at least 80% of its assets in or with economic characteristics similar to these index securities. It operates as a non-diversified investment vehicle.

name: Xtrackers Cybersecurity Select Equity ETF
description_original: The fund, using a “passive” or indexing investment approach, seeks investment results that correspond generally to the performance, before fees and expenses, of the underlying index, which is comprised of companies that have business operations in the field of cybersecurity and that fulfill certain sustainability criteria. The fund is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
PSWD tracks a market cap-weighted index of companies globally that are engaged in the cybersecurity industry. The index screens securities based on various ESG criteria provided by Sustainalytics.

PSWD targets ESG companies in the global cybersecurity industry. The fund selects from a universe of global equities of any capitalization. Eligible firms must meet size and liquidity requirements and have business exposure in these industries: a) carrier edge network management equipment, b) customer premises network security equipment, c) colocation and data center services, d) government IT services, e) network security access policy software, and f) network security software, as classified by FactSet RBICS. Securities listed in China, Egypt, India, Pakistan, or Russia are excluded. The index then applies ESG screens to remove companies that are non-compliant with the UNGC principles, have an ESG risk score of 40 or higher, and are involved in controversial and conventional weapons, tobacco, thermal coal, and oil and gas. From the remaining list, the largest 50 stocks are selected and weighted by market cap, subject to a maximum weight of 4.5% for each security.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks investment results that correspond generally to the performance, before fees and expenses, of the Solactive Cyber Security ESG Screened Index. The fund, using a “passive” or indexing investment approach, seeks investment results that correspond generally to the performance, before fees and expenses, of the underlying index, which is comprised of companies that have business operations in the field of cybersecurity and that fulfill certain sustainability criteria. The fund is non-diversified.

The fund includes pharmaceutical companies, biotech companies, drug manufacturers, diagnostics companies, wholesalers or distributors of biopharma products, and biopharma service providers. It is worth noting that manufacturers of pharmaceutical ingredients are excluded, as the fund focuses on innovation in the sector. CHNA uses a tiered weighting system. The index is reconstituted on every second Monday of each February and August.
merged_description: This ETF invested in companies primarily involved in the growth of China's pharmaceutical and biotech related industries, seeking to track the performance of a modified equal-weighted index. The index underlying the ETF was reconstituted semi-annually.

name: EA Series Trust ARK 21Shares Ac
description_original: The fund is an actively managed exchange-traded fund. Under normal market conditions, the fund will seek to achieve its investment objective by investing in a portfolio of bitcoin futures contracts. The fund is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
ARKA is actively managed, seeking capital appreciation through a portfolio comprised of USD, cash-settled Bitcoin (BTC) futures contracts. The fund does not directly invest in Bitcoin or other digital assets and refrains from maintaining direct exposure to its spot price.

ARKA holds standardized, cash-settled Bitcoin futures traded on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange (CME). With a targeted allocation of over 25% of total assets, the fund operates through a subsidiary structure based in the Cayman Islands. The fund employs a rolling strategy that seeks optimal roll yield by investing in contracts with the most attractive combination of cost, liquidity, and other relevant factors. Typically, these contracts have monthly or quarterly contract periods. Moreover, the fund may invest in front-month Bitcoin futures contracts and usually rolls to the next nearby contracts at the time believed to generate the greatest roll yield. To provide liquidity and collateral for Bitcoin Futures investments, the remaining assets are diversified into short-term cash instruments, including U.S. Treasury securities and money market instruments. Additionally, the fund may engage in leveraging through reverse repurchase agreements.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks capital appreciation. The fund is an actively managed exchange-traded fund. Under normal market conditions, the fund will seek to achieve its investment objective by investing in a portfolio of bitcoin futures contracts. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This actively managed exchange-traded fund seeks capital appreciation by primarily investing in a portfolio of cash-settled Bitcoin futures contracts traded on the CME under normal market conditions. It does not invest directly in Bitcoin or other digital assets and aims to avoid direct exposure to the spot price. The fund employs a rolling strategy focused on achieving optimal roll yield using typically monthly or quarterly contracts and strategically rolling positions. While targeting a significant allocation to futures, it also holds short-term cash instruments like U.S. Treasury securities and money market instruments for liquidity and collateral. The fund is non-diversified, may operate through a subsidiary structure, and may utilize leveraging through reverse repurchase agreements.

name: Invesco S&P Spin-Off ETF
description_original: The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise the underlying index. The underlying index is designed to measure the performance of U.S. companies that have been spun off from a parent company within the past four years. The fund is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
CSD tracks an index of mostly large- and mid-cap US equities that have broken away from their parent firms in the last 4 years.

CSD offers niche equity exposure to spin-offs. The idea: A firm spun off from a larger parent has a singular focus on its core business, rather than being a rudderless component of a larger whole. Its S&P index uses a 4-year look back, and names can be added immediately once the monthly reconstitution rolls around. Single-name exposure can be concentrated up to 7% at rebalance. CSD pulls from a broad US index (not from the S&P 500) but screens out smaller firms with a minimum $1B market-cap screen. It applies no additional selection screens, however, thus offering reasonably pure-play exposure to its narrow thesis. Note: Prior to May 20, 2016, CSD tracked the Beacon Spin-off Index, which used different time horizons and had a growth-oriented multi-factor selection process. The change was material but the spin-off thesis remains the same.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the investment results (before fees and expenses) of the S&P U.S. Spin-Off Index (the "underlying index"). The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in securities that comprise the underlying index. The underlying index is designed to measure the performance of U.S. companies that have been spun off from a parent company within the past four years. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This fund seeks to track the performance of U.S. companies spun off from a parent firm within the past four years, following the S&P U.S. Spin-Off Index. It typically invests at least 90% of its assets in the index's securities. The investment concept provides niche, pure-play exposure based on the thesis that spin-offs benefit from a singular business focus. Composed primarily of large- and mid-cap US equities, the index selects companies from a broad U.S. universe with a minimum $1 billion market capitalization, applying no further selection screens beyond the spin-off criteria. Constituents are added upon monthly reconstitution, with single-name concentration capped at rebalance, generally up to 7%. The fund is considered non-diversified.

name: The Consumer Staples Select Sector SPDR Fund
description_original: The Consumer Staples Select Sector SPDR Fund seeks to provide investment results that, before expenses, correspond generally to the price and yield performance of the Consumer Staples Select Sector Index (the “Index”)The Index seeks to provide an effective representation of the consumer staples sector of the S&P 500 IndexSeeks to provide precise exposure to companies from consumer staples distribution & retail; household products; food products; beverages; tobacco; and personal care products industries in the U.S.Allows investors to take strategic or tactical positions at a more targeted level than traditional style based investing
description_eftcom:
XLP tracks a market-cap-weighted index of consumer-staples stocks drawn from the S&P 500.

XLP delivers a representative if slightly conservative basket of consumer-staples firms. Because XLP pulls its stocks from the S&P 500 rather than the broad market, it holds far fewer names than our benchmark, producing somewhat-concentrated exposure. The fund's holdings are nearly all large-caps, which investors may appreciate for their familiarity and stability. XLP seeks to provide exposure to stocks in the following industries: food and staples retailing, beverage, food products, tobacco, household and personal products. The index is reconstituted and rebalanced on a quarterly basis.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to provide investment results that, before expenses, correspond generally to the price and yield performance of publicly traded equity securities of companies in the Consumer Staples Select Sector Index. In seeking to track the performance of the index, the fund employs a replication strategy. It generally invests substantially all, but at least 95%, of its total assets in the securities comprising the index. The index includes companies that have been identified as Consumer Staples companies by the GICS®. It is non-diversified.
merged_description: This ETF seeks to provide investment results that generally correspond to the price and yield performance of a market-cap-weighted index representing the consumer staples sector of the S&P 500 Index. Utilizing a replication strategy, the fund typically invests substantially all of its assets (at least 95%) in the securities of the underlying index. The index focuses on companies within specific consumer staples industries, including food and staples retailing, beverages, food products, tobacco, and household and personal products. By drawing stocks from the S&P 500, the fund holds a more concentrated basket of predominantly large-cap firms compared to broader market benchmarks, resulting in a non-diversified portfolio. The underlying index is reconstituted and rebalanced quarterly, aiming to offer investors targeted exposure to this segment of the U.S. equity market.

name: ALPS Disruptive Technologies ETF
description_original: The fund will invest at least 80% of its net assets in securities that comprise the underlying index. The underlying index is designed to identify the companies using disruptive technologies in each of ten thematic areas: Healthcare Innovation, Internet of Things, Clean Energy and Smart Grid, Cloud Computing, Data and Analytics, FinTech, Robotics and Artificial Intelligence, Cybersecurity, 3D Printing, and Mobile Payments.
description_eftcom:
DTEC tracks an index of 100 global companies that are involved in disruptive technologies across 10 themes.

DTEC covers 10 different themes within the tech sectorhealthcare innovation, internet of things, clean energy & smart grid, cloud computing, data & analytics, fintech, robotics & AI, cybersecurity, 3D printing, and mobile paymentsall with a focus on disruptive technologies and innovation. The index selects 10 companies from each theme according to a proprietary model and equally weights each security. This effectively gives each theme and each company equal representation. The fund is not limited to a specific geography and can select companies from developed and emerging markets alike. The index is reconstituted annually and rebalanced quarterly.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks investment results that correspond (before fees and expenses) generally to the performance of the Indxx Disruptive Technologies Index (the "underlying index"). name: Invesco S&P SmallCap Momentum ETF
description_original: The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise the underlying index. Strictly in accordance with its guidelines and mandated procedures, the index provider compiles, maintains and calculates the underlying index, which is composed of constituents of the S&P SmallCap 600® that have the highest momentum score.
description_eftcom: XSMO offers a momentum take on US small-caps culled from the S&P SmallCap 600, a market-cap-weighted index that consists of US small-cap companies screened for size, liquidity, and financial viability. The underlying index selects approximately 120 names with the highest momentum score, derived from 12-month performance excluding the most recent month and favors stocks with lower volatility. Selected securities are weighted by a combination of market cap and momentum score, and are constrained such that individual securities will not exceed 9% weight of the portfolio and three times its market cap in the index universe. Prior to June 24, 2019 the fund tracked a Russell growth index under a different name and ticker (PXSG).
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the investment results (before fees and expenses) of the S&P SmallCap 600 Momentum Index (the "underlying index"). name: OneAscent Emerging Markets ETF
description_original: Under normal market conditions, the fund will invest at least 80% of its total assets (plus borrowings for investment purposes) in equity securities of non-U.S. companies in emerging market countries, including common stocks, depositary receipts evidencing ownership of common stocks, preferred stocks, securities convertible into common stocks, and securities that carry the right to buy common stocks (e.g., rights and warrants).
description_eftcom:
OAEM actively invests in an equity portfolio of large-, mid-, and small-cap emerging market companies. The fund combines an ESG screening methodology with its fundamental investment process.

OAEM holds a high conviction portfolio of emerging market equities. The fund expects to invest in at least three countries and may include depositary receipts, preferred stocks, convertibles, rights, and warrants in its equity investments. It uses a values-based screening process, which first excludes companies involved in controversial activities from the investable universe and then identifies companies with positive ESG impact. The fund adviser combines quantitative analysis and bottom-up fundamental research to consider the corporate life-cycle spectrum and identify companies that can generate sustainable returns on investment. OAEM seeks to invest across all parts of the life-cycle spectrum and hold high-growth, high-return, income-oriented and distressed investments. The fund adviser may use forwards, swaps, or futures to hedge foreign currency exposure and utilize options or total return swaps to hedge equity exposure.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to achieve long-term capital appreciation. merged_description: This ETF seeks long-term capital appreciation through active investment in emerging market equity securities. Under normal market conditions, it invests at least 80% of its assets in non-U.S. companies located in emerging countries, targeting large-, mid-, and small-cap ranges and typically holding a high conviction portfolio across at least three countries. Its holdings primarily include common stocks, but may also consist of depositary receipts, preferred stocks, convertibles, rights, and warrants. The investment process integrates a values-based ESG screening method, which excludes controversial companies and identifies those with positive impact, with bottom-up fundamental research that evaluates the corporate life-cycle to seek companies capable of generating sustainable returns. name: iShares Cloud 5G and Tech ETF
description_original: The fund will invest at least 80% of its assets in the component securities of the index and in investments that have economic characteristics that are substantially identical to the component securities of the index and may invest up to 10% of its assets in certain futures, options and swap contracts, cash and cash equivalents. description_eftcom:
IDAT tracks an index of global technology companies that focus on two primary themes: cloud computing and 5G. Holdings are weighted by market-cap within each theme.

IDAT targets global digital infrastructure technology providers which are specifically identified by Morningstars research team as companies that benefit from having significant exposure to two primary themes: cloud computing and 5G. Eligible firms that meet size and liquidity screens are further evaluated based on their current and projected 5-, 10-, and 20-year revenue from cloud computing- and 5G-related businesses. Companies are then scored based on their given betas relative to each theme.The top 25 companies within each primary theme are selected and weighted by market-cap. Individual positions are capped at 2.5% weight. Holdings are rebalanced and reconstituted annually to have equal allocations on each primary theme group.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the investment results of the Morningstar® Global Digital Infrastructure & Connectivity IndexSM composed of companies from developed and emerging markets that could benefit from providing products, services, and technologies related to cloud computing and 5G. The index components are selected based on a research process that identifies global technology companies with significant current and projected revenue exposure to these themes, screening for size and liquidity before selecting top companies for each theme based on their scoring. Holdings within the index are weighted by market capitalization within each theme, with individual positions capped, and the index is annually rebalanced to maintain equal allocation between the cloud computing and 5G themes. The fund invests at least 80% of its assets in the securities that make up this index or investments with substantially identical economic characteristics, and is considered non-diversified.

name: ProShares MSCI Transformational Changes ETF
description_original: The index selects companies which may benefit from transformational changes in how people work, take care of their health, and consume and connect ("Transformational Changes") - changes accelerated by COVID-19. The fund will generally use a “replication strategy” to achieve its investment objective, meaning that it will invest in all of the component securities of the index in approximately the same proportion as the index.
description_eftcom:
ANEW tracks a market-cap-weighted index of global stocks that benefit from transformational changes in peoples work, health care, consumption, and connection.

ANEW provides exposure to firms that derive the bulk of their revenues from four transformational change themes Future of Work, Digital Consumer, Food Revolution, and Genomics and Telehealth. The relevant firms from multi-sectors involve cybersecurity, cloud computing, internet of things, machine learning and AI, e-gaming, social media, plant-based foods, agricultural and food delivery technology, gene editing and therapy, biosecurity and zoonotic disease (disease transmitted between animals and humans) mitigation, bio hardware, bioinformatics, and digital health and remote care. These firms may come from 23 Developed and 26 Emerging Market countries. The index selects stocks by assigning a Relevance Score using natural language processing for keyword searches relating to the themes and is weighted by the Relevance Score and market cap. The four themes are equally weighted with each stock subject to a 2% cap. The Index undergoes semi-annual review starting each May.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks investment results, before fees and expenses, that track the performance of the MSCI Global Transformational Changes Index (the "index"). The fund invests in financial instruments that ProShare Advisors believes, in combination, should track the performance of the index. The index is designed to measure the performance of companies associated with one or more of the following themes: Future of Work, Digital Consumer, Genomic & Telehealth, and Food Revolution. Under normal circumstances, it will invest at least 80% of its total assets in components of the index or in instruments with similar economic characteristics.
merged_description: This fund aims to track the performance of a global index that focuses on companies expected to benefit from significant transformational changes reshaping how people work, manage their health, consume goods, and connect. The underlying index identifies companies worldwide, across both developed and emerging markets, categorized into four key, equally-weighted themes: Future of Work, Digital Consumer, Genomic & Telehealth, and Food Revolution. A unique selection process, employing natural language processing, assesses companies' relevance to these themes. The fund typically invests in the index's component securities, providing exposure to firms heavily involved in areas such as cybersecurity, cloud computing, AI, e-gaming, plant-based foods, agricultural technology, gene editing, and digital health.

name: iShares Global Financials ETF
description_original: The fund generally invests at least 80% of its assets in the component securities of its underlying index and in investments that have economic characteristics that are substantially identical to the component securities of its underlying index and may invest up to 20% of its assets in certain futures, options and swap contracts, cash and cash equivalents. The index measures the performance of companies that the index provider deems to be part of the financials sector of the economy and that the index provider believes are important to global markets.
description_eftcom:
IXG tracks a market cap-weighted index of large- and mid-cap global financial stocks.

IXG is a high-beta play on global financials, due in large part to the fund's heavier concentration versus our benchmark. Despite the fact that IXG holds many of the same stocks in its top 10 as our benchmark, its far smaller basket means that large-cap banks and insurance companies are held in greater weights. As one might expect, IXG carries an elevated beta and tilts hard toward large-caps. IXG can be traded fairly with some care. Daily volume is robust and spreads are manageable. The fund's liquid basket is good news for larger investors seeking to trade in bulk. IXG is also an incredibly Efficient fund. It recovers almost all of its already-reasonable fee, tracking its index almost perfectly. Overall, IXG is a cost-effective and reasonably liquid way to access global financials, at the expense of some added concentration.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the investment results of the S&P Global 1200 Financials IndexTM. While tracking this broad global index, the fund's portfolio exhibits heavier concentration and a strong tilt towards large-cap banks and insurance firms, contributing to its elevated beta as a high-beta play on global financials. The fund is considered relatively liquid, featuring robust daily volume and manageable spreads, and is noted for its efficiency in tracking its underlying index closely.

name: Matthews Asia Innovators Active ETF

name: First Trust Nasdaq Transportation ETF

merged_description: This investment aims to track a Nasdaq index focused on the U.S. transportation sector by investing at least 90% of its assets in the index's securities, which include common stocks and depository receipts. The underlying index targets a concentrated portfolio of approximately 30 of the most liquid U.S. transportation companies, spanning various segments such as railroads, airlines, trucking, and shipping. Companies are initially selected based on liquidity and then weighted according to a strategy that ranks them based on a combination of three factors: strong growth (evaluated by price returns), attractive value (assessed by cash flow-to-price), and low volatility (based on historical price fluctuations). The resulting non-diversified portfolio includes a rule limiting any single holding to a maximum of 8%, and the index undergoes annual reconstitution and quarterly rebalancing.

name: Pacer US Small Cap Cash Cows Growth Leaders ETF
description_original: A strategy-driven exchange traded fund that aims to identify top growth companies in the S&P SmallCap 600 Index by screening for above average free cash flow margins.
description_eftcom:
CAFG tracks a price momentum-weighted index of 100 small-cap US companies that exhibit the highest growth characteristics.

CAFG utilizes a rules-based methodology in constructing its view for a quality stock portfolio. Beginning with the S&P SmallCap 600, and excluding the stocks in the financial and real estate sectors, the fund identifies top growth securities by screening for above-average projected free cash flows and earnings over the next two years. The securities are then ranked by their trailing 12-month free cash flow margin, and the top 100 stocks are selected. The theory is that stocks with the highest free cash flow margin over time may produce higher current and future sales and earnings growth. Index holdings are weighted based on 6-month price momentum with a 5% capping on each company for diversification purposes. The index rebalancing and reconstitution are done quarterly in March, June, September, and December.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the performance, before fees and expenses, of the Pacer US Small Cap Cash Cows Growth Leaders Index (the “index”). The index uses a rules-based methodology that seeks to provide exposure to small-capitalization U.S. companies with above average free cash flow margins. Under normal circumstances, the fund will seek to invest at least 80% of its net assets, plus the amount of any borrowings for investment purposes, in securities of small-capitalization companies (“small cap”) that are principally traded in the United States. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This exchange traded fund tracks a rules-based index focused on identifying growth leaders among small-capitalization U.S. companies. Utilizing a methodology that begins with the S&P SmallCap 600 and excludes financials and real estate, the strategy screens for companies exhibiting strong growth characteristics based on above-average projected free cash flow and earnings over the next two years. Companies are then ranked by their trailing 12-month free cash flow margin, with the top 100 selected for the index. These holdings are weighted based on their 6-month price momentum, subject to a 5% company cap, and the index is rebalanced quarterly. The fund primarily invests at least 80% of its assets in these small-cap U.S. securities and is classified as non-diversified.

name: Xtrackers S&P MidCap 400 ESG ETF
description_original: The index seeks to target 75% of the float market capitalization (i.e., the amount of stock which is available for trading by the general public) of each Global Industry Classification Standard Industry Group (“GICS Industry Group”) within the S&P MidCap 400 Index, using an ESG score as the defining characteristic. The fund will invest at least 80% of its total assets (but typically far more) in component securities of the index. It is non-diversified.
description_eftcom: MIDE adds an ESG layer to the S&P mid-cap 400. It seeks to capture US mid-caps with high ESG scores within each GICS sector, while maintaining the sector weights of the S&P 400. MIDE screens out companies involved in tobacco, controversial weapons and thermal coal. Companies are also excluded if they fall in the bottom 5% of the United Nations Global Compact (UNGC) score ranking or in the bottom 25% of ESG scores within each GICS sector as rated by SAM. Inclusion of constituents flagged for risks involving controversial issues is subject for review by the Index Committee. The index is market cap-weighted and rebalances on an annual basis. On February 10, 2025, both the fund and its index dropped and replaced ESG name claims with Scored and Screened. The change has no effect on the funds strategy.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks investment results that correspond generally to the performance, before fees and expenses, of the S&P MidCap 400 ESG Index. The index seeks to target 75% of the float-adjusted market capitalization (i.e., the amount of stock that is available for trading by the general public) of each GICS Industry Group within the S&P MidCap 400 Index, using the ESG scores assigned to the companies in the Eligible Universe by the index provider as the determining factor. The fund will invest at least 80% of its total assets (but typically far more) in component securities of the index.
merged_description: This ETF seeks to track the performance of an index based on the S&P MidCap 400, focusing on US mid-capitalization companies. The index targets approximately 75% of the float-adjusted market capitalization within each GICS Industry Group or sector of the S&P MidCap 400. Company selection is primarily based on ESG scores within each sector, aiming for higher scores while maintaining sector weights similar to the parent index. Specific screening criteria exclude companies involved in tobacco, controversial weapons, and thermal coal, as well as those with low UNGC or sector ESG scores. The index is market cap-weighted and rebalanced annually. The fund invests at least 80% of its assets in index securities and is considered non-diversified. Note that the fund's description has recently been updated to reflect its "Scored and Screened" methodology, though the investment strategy remains unchanged.

name: VanEck ChiNext ETF
description_original: The fund normally invests at least 80% of its total assets in securities that comprise the fund's benchmark index. The index is a free-float adjusted index intended to track the performance of the 100 largest and most liquid stocks listed and trading on the ChiNext Market of the Shenzhen Stock Exchange. The index is comprised of China A-shares (“A-shares”).
description_eftcom: CNXT is one of the more innovative China ETFs to launch in years. Its a highly niche-y ETF that targets 100 of the largest stocks listed on Shenzhens SME and ChiNext Boards, which cater to smaller- and medium-size enterprise companies. Many companies included in the index tilt toward tech and consumer-related companies and startups needing less stringent listing requirements. CNXT is part of a new class of China funds called RQFII ETFs, which directly hold mainland-listed shares through a quota system. Prior to Dec. 10, 2021, the fund was named VanEck Vectors ChinaAMC SME-ChiNext ETF and tracked the SME-ChiNext 100 Index.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to replicate as closely as possible, before fees and expenses, the price and yield performance of the ChiNext Index. The fund normally invests at least 80% of its total assets in securities that comprise the fund's benchmark index. The index is a free-float adjusted index intended to track the performance of the 100 largest and most liquid stocks listed and trading on the ChiNext Market of the Shenzhen Stock Exchange. The index is comprised of China A-shares (“A-shares”).
merged_description: This investment seeks to replicate as closely as possible the performance of the ChiNext Index, which tracks the 100 largest and most liquid China A-shares listed on the ChiNext Market of the Shenzhen Stock Exchange. This market caters to smaller- and medium-size enterprise companies and startups, often with a tilt towards technology and consumer sectors. The fund normally invests at least 80% of its total assets in securities that comprise this index and operates as part of a new class of China funds that directly hold mainland-listed shares through a quota system.

name: JPMorgan Inflation Managed Bond ETF
description_original: Under normal circumstances, the fund will invest at least 80% of its “Assets” in bonds. “Assets” means net assets, plus the amount of borrowings for investment purposes. As part of its main investment strategy, it may principally invest in corporate bonds, U.S. government and agency debt securities, asset-backed securities, and mortgage-related and mortgage-backed securities.
description_eftcom:
JCPI aims to protect total return by holding a broad portfolio of US investment-grade bonds that is equivalent to those of inflation-protected securities. The actively managed fund makes use of swaps to hedge inflation risk.

JCPI aims to maximize total return by providing exposure to USD-denominated investment-grade bonds. The words Inflation Managed in the funds name refers to its strategy of creating a portfolio equivalent to those of inflation-protected securities and does not necessarily reflect the type of securities it invests in. The fund uses swaps to hedge inflation risk based on the CPI-U Index that measures price changes of a basket of goods and services purchased by urban consumers. The fund may invest in various corporate and government bonds, as well as actual Treasury Inflation Protected Securities, that are perceived to perform well over market cycles. The fund may invest up to 10% in junk bonds. As the fund uses derivatives, it could open investors to potential counterparty risk. On Apr. 8, 2022, JCPI converted from a mutual fund called JPMorgan Inflation Managed Bond Fund to an actively managed ETF structure, starting with $1.1 billion in net assets.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to maximize inflation protected total return. Under normal circumstances, the fund will invest at least 80% of its “Assets” in bonds. “Assets” means net assets, plus the amount of borrowings for investment purposes. As part of its main investment strategy, it may principally invest in corporate bonds, U.S. government and agency debt securities, asset-backed securities, and mortgage-related and mortgage-backed securities.
merged_description: This actively managed ETF seeks to maximize inflation-protected total return by holding a broad portfolio of US investment-grade bonds equivalent to those of inflation-protected securities. Under normal circumstances, it invests at least 80% of its assets, defined as net assets plus borrowings for investment purposes, in bonds. The fund may principally invest in corporate bonds, U.S. government and agency debt securities, asset-backed securities, and mortgage-related/backed securities. While it may invest in actual Treasury Inflation Protected Securities, the core strategy for hedging inflation risk based on the CPI-U index is achieved through the use of swaps. The fund may allocate up to 10% to junk bonds, and the use of derivatives like swaps introduces potential counterparty risk.

name: AI Powered International Equity ETF
description_original: The fund is actively managed and seeks to achieve its investment objective by investing primarily in equity securities (or depositary receipts) of companies in developed markets outside the United States based on the results of a proprietary, quantitative model (the "EquBot Model") developed by the adviser that runs on the Watson™ platform. Its investment adviser is a technology based company focused on applying artificial intelligence ("AI") based solutions to investment analyses. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This actively managed fund seeks its investment objective by primarily investing in equity securities and depositary receipts of companies located in developed markets outside the United States. Its unique investment strategy relies on a proprietary, quantitative model developed by its technology-based adviser, which focuses on applying artificial intelligence (AI) solutions to investment analysis. This model operates on the Watson™ platform. The fund is classified as non-diversified.

name: FlexShares ESG & Climate Emerging Markets Core Index Fund
description_original: The index is designed to reflect the performance of a selection of companies that exhibit certain ESG characteristics, while also seeking to provide broad-market, core exposure to publicly traded equity securities issued by companies domiciled in emerging market countries. The fund will invest at least 80% of its total assets in the securities of the index and in ADRs and GDRs based on the securities in the index. It is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
FEEM tracks a principles-based index of large-cap companies in emerging markets that exhibit positive environmental, social, and corporate governance (ESG) characteristics. A proprietary ESG scoring system is used to select and weight holdings.

The Fund will be closing.The last day of trading will be on April 23, 2024. FEEM follows an index designed to provide a broad exposure to emerging market companies that exhibit several specific environmental, social, and corporate governance attributes. Selection begins with the constituents of the Northern Trust Emerging Markets Large Cap Index. Each eligible company is ranked based on their ESG scores as measured by their ability to manage risks associated with material ESG issues and their good corporate governance score. Moreover, the fund also utilizes carbon-related risk metrics to assess the carbon emissions intensity, carbon reserves, and carbon risk exposure for each firm. Companies are also screened and excluded based on business activities that produce negative impacts in the environment. Additional optimization is also done to minimize systematic risk including constituent, liquidity, absolute weight, sector, industry group, and turnover constraints. The index is reconstituted on a quarterly basis
merged_description: This ETF tracks an index designed to provide exposure to a selection of large-cap companies in emerging markets that exhibit positive environmental, social, and corporate governance (ESG) characteristics. Leveraging a proprietary scoring system, the index assesses companies based on their ESG performance, including governance, risk management, and carbon risk, while screening out those associated with negative environmental impacts. The approach aims for core emerging market exposure via this principles-based filter and employs optimization techniques to manage portfolio risks. The fund is considered non-diversified and invests at least 80% of its assets in index securities. The underlying index is reconstituted quarterly. It is important to note that this fund is scheduled to close, with its last day of trading being April 23, 2024.

name: Goldman Sachs North American Pipelines & Power Equity ETF
description_original: The fund seeks to achieve its investment objective by investing at least 80% of its assets in securities included in its underlying index. The index is designed to deliver exposure to equity securities of U.S. and Canadian listed companies, including companies structured as master limited partnerships, operating in the pipelines and power universe. The fund is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
GPOW tracks an index comprised of North American companies engaged in pipelines and the alternative wholesale power segment. The fund weighs securities by a multi-factor process based on growth and quality.

The security was delisted. The last of trading on an exchange is January 10, 2025. GPOW invests in US and Canadian companies that provide broad energy infrastructure exposure, including MLPs and pure-play companies tied to the alternative wholesale power segment. MLP investments are limited to 25% of the funds assets. Eligible securities must meet the necessary size and trading volume and have core businesses in midstream energy, oil and gas transportation and infrastructure, LPG, and propane, as classified by FactSet RBICS. Remaining securities are then given a fundamental score multiplier, applying growth and quality factors that tilt weighting to firms whose scores are fundamentally higher than their peers. The weighting strategy consists of seven sub-factors: implied total return, EPS growth, medium term trading momentum, leverage, cash flow and balance sheet accruals, and return on capital. The index rebalances quarterly.
merged_description: This ETF seeks to provide exposure to North American companies operating in the pipelines, energy infrastructure, and power universe, including alternative wholesale power. It invests primarily in US and Canadian listed equities, including master limited partnerships, limiting MLP exposure to 25% of assets. Companies are weighted based on a multi-factor process utilizing growth and quality criteria derived from fundamental analysis. The fund is non-diversified.

name: Direxion Nanotechnology ETF
description_original: The fund, under normal circumstances, invests at least 80% of its assets in the securities that comprise the index or investments with economic characteristics similar to the securities included in the index. The index is provided by S&P Dow Jones Indices LLC (the “index provider”) and is designed to measure the performance of U.S.-listed securities, including depositary receipts, of companies involved in the nanotechnology industry. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This fund is designed to track the performance of an index that measures U.S.-listed securities, including depositary receipts, of companies involved in the nanotechnology industry. Under normal circumstances, it invests at least 80% of its assets in the securities that comprise this index or investments with similar economic characteristics. Provided by S&P Dow Jones Indices LLC, the index serves as the benchmark for the fund's strategy. Notably, the fund is classified as non-diversified.

name: Fidelity Disruptors ETF
description_original: The fund normally invests its assets in a combination of five Fidelity® funds, each of which normally invests in equity securities of companies that represent a disruptive theme. Fidelity's disruptive strategies seek to identify innovative developments that could signal new directions for delivering products and services to customers. Generally, these companies have or are developing new or unconventional ways of doing business that could disrupt and displace incumbents over time.
description_eftcom:
FDIF is an actively managed fund-of-funds that holds a suite of global Fidelity ETFs, all of which are tied with disruptive technologies in automation, communications, finance, medicine, and technology.

FDIF seeks long-term capital growth through equal investments in five Fidelity ETFs globally. The holdings of this ETF comprises tickers: FBOT, FDCF, FDFF, FMED, and FDXT, each one utilizing Fidelitys disruptive strategies in identifying companies involved in disruptive technologies that represent automation, communications, finance, medicine, and technology themes, respectively. Disruptive technologies are innovations that may reshape how businesses currently deliver their services and operate, potentially displacing industry leaders over time. The fund does not trade actively, therefore, does not take advantage of market opportunities. When using a fund-of-funds wrapper, total fees should be accounted for. FDIF converted from a mutual fund called Fidelity Disruptors Fund to an ETF structure starting with $104 million in net assets.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks long-term growth of capital. The fund normally invests its assets in a combination of five Fidelity® Funds, each of which normally invests in equity securities of companies that represent a disruptive theme. Fidelity's disruptive strategies seek to identify innovative developments that could signal new directions for delivering products and services to customers. Generally, these companies have or are developing new or unconventional ways of doing business that could disrupt and displace incumbents over time.
merged_description: This fund aims for long-term capital growth by investing in a combination of five underlying funds. Each of these funds typically focuses on equity securities of companies representing a specific disruptive theme: automation, communications, finance, medicine, and technology. The strategy identifies companies with innovative developments and unconventional business methods that may reshape how services are delivered and potentially displace industry leaders over time. The overall investment approach maintains an equal allocation across these five core disruptive themes.

name: Teucrium Wheat Fund
description_original: The fund seeks to achieve its investment objective by investing in Benchmark Component Futures Contracts. Under normal market conditions, the manager expects that 100% of the fund’s assets will be invested in benchmark component futures contracts and in cash and cash equivalents.
description_eftcom:
WEAT tracks an index of wheat futures contracts. It reflects the performance of wheat by holding Chicago Board of Trade wheat futures contracts with three different expiration dates.

WEAT avoids the front-month contract in its aim to provide exposure to wheat futures. Instead it holds the 2nd to expiration, 3rd to expiration and the subsequent December contracts to mitigate the impact of contango, weighting the contracts 35%, 30% and 35%, respectively. This approach should have some success in contango mitigation but may lag front month at times. The fund's structure means a K-1 at tax time and a blended tax rate.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to provide investors with a cost-efficient way to gain price exposure to the wheat market for future delivery. The fund seeks to achieve its investment objective by investing in Benchmark Component Futures Contracts. Under normal market conditions, the manager expects that 100% of the fund’s assets will be invested in benchmark component futures contracts and in cash and cash equivalents.
merged_description: This ETF seeks to provide investors with price exposure to the wheat market for future delivery by investing in Chicago Board of Trade (CBOT) wheat futures contracts. Its core strategy involves avoiding the front-month contract to mitigate the impact of contango, instead holding a weighted portfolio of contracts second-to-expiration (35%), third-to-expiration (30%), and the subsequent December contract (35%). Under normal market conditions, the fund expects to invest 100% of its assets in these benchmark component futures contracts and cash equivalents. While this approach aims to manage contango, it may at times lag the performance of the front-month contract. Investors should note that the fund's structure results in a K-1 at tax time with a blended tax rate.

name: Invesco S&P 500 Equal Weight Consumer Discretionary ETF
description_original: The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise the underlying index. The underlying index is composed of all of the components of the S&P 500® Consumer Discretionary Index, an index that contains the common stocks of all companies included in the S&P 500® Index that are classified as members of the consumer discretionary sector, as defined according to the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS).
description_eftcom:
RSPD tracks an equal-weighted index of large-cap US Consumer Discretionary stocks drawn from the S&P 500.

RSPD provides a unique but not radical alternative to market-cap-weighted consumer discretionary exposure in the US. Basically, the fund equal-weights all stocks in the S&P 500 Consumer Discretionary Index, whose composition is determined by an S&P Committee. Equal-weighting avoids concentration in large firms, while significantly increasing midcap exposure compared to the broad sector. RSPD's tilt toward smaller firms is limited by its universethe S&P 500which excludes small-caps. The index is rebalanced quarterly. Prior to June 7, 2023, the fund traded under the ticker RCD.
merged_description: This ETF seeks to track the performance of an equal-weighted index composed of large-capitalization U.S. companies classified within the consumer discretionary sector of the S&P 500 Index, as defined by the Global Industry Classification Standard (GICS). By utilizing an equal-weighting methodology rather than market capitalization, the fund aims to avoid concentration in the largest companies and provide increased exposure to mid-sized firms within the large-cap segment. The fund generally invests at least 90% of its total assets in the securities that comprise this underlying index, which is rebalanced quarterly.

name: Direxion Daily Healthcare Bull 3X Shares
description_original: The fund invests at least 80% of its net assets in financial instruments, such as swap agreements, securities of the index, and ETFs that track the index and other financial instruments that provide daily leveraged exposure to the index or to ETFs that track the index. The index includes domestic companies from the healthcare sector, which includes: pharmaceuticals; health care equipment and supplies; health care providers and services; biotechnology; life sciences tools and services; and etc. It is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
CURE provides 3x levered exposure to a market cap weighted sub-index of the S&P 500 that tracks the performance of US listed health care companies.

As a levered product, CURE is not a buy-and-hold ETF, it's a short-term tactical instrument. Like many levered funds, it delivers 3x exposure only for one day. Over longer periods, returns can vary significantly from 3x of its underlying index, which covers some of the biggest healthcare nameslike J&J, Pfizer, and Merckin the space, and those heavyweights comprise a large share of CURE's cap-weighted, S&P 500-only portfolio. As a short-term product, CURE's expense ratio is less important than all in trading costs. Trading can be volatile. Check the latest Tradability data on this page.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks daily investment results, before fees and expenses, of 300% of the daily performance of the Health Care Select Sector Index. The fund invests at least 80% of its net assets in financial instruments, that, in combination, provide 3X daily leveraged exposure to the index, consistent with the fund's investment objective. The index includes domestic companies from the healthcare sector, which includes: pharmaceuticals; health care equipment and supplies; health care providers and services; biotechnology; life sciences tools and services; and health care technology. It is non-diversified.
merged_description: This ETF is designed to provide daily investment results that are 300% of the performance of the Health Care Select Sector Index. It aims to achieve this 3x daily leveraged exposure by investing at least 80% of its net assets in financial instruments such as swaps and securities tied to the index or index-tracking ETFs. The underlying index tracks domestic companies within the U.S. healthcare sector, including pharmaceuticals, equipment, services, and biotechnology, and is market-cap weighted with significant concentration in major industry names. It is crucial to note that this fund is intended as a short-term tactical instrument suitable for single-day use only; its returns over periods longer than one day may differ significantly from three times the index performance, making it unsuitable for a buy-and-hold strategy. The fund is non-diversified and trading can potentially be volatile.

name: iShares ESG MSCI USA Min Vol Factor ETF
description_original: The underlying index is designed to measure the performance of large- and mid-capitalization U.S. equity securities that reflect the performance of a minimum volatility strategy and, relative to the MSCI USA Index, have higher favorable ESG characteristics and lower carbon exposure. The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its assets in the component securities of the underlying index and may invest up to 10% of its assets in certain futures, options and swap contracts, cash and cash equivalents. It is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
ESMV tracks an index of large- and mid-cap US stocks that have low volatility and positive ESG characteristics.

ESMV is a passively managed ETF that provides exposure to large- and mid-cap US stocks that have low volatility, reduced carbon exposure, and positive ESG characteristics. The fund selects stocks from its parent index, the MSCI USA Index, and excludes those associated with tobacco, controversial weapons, civilian firearms, and certain climate change-related activities, as well as those involved in severe business controversies. Severe business controversies are based on MSCI ESG Controversy Scores. Companies without a controversy score or not assessed by the index provider are also excluded. Securities are rated and ranked in comparison to industry peers based on ESG characteristics and resilience to ESG risks to their industry. The fund then applies an optimizer to select and weight securities, aiming to achieve lower volatility and better ESG qualities relative to the parent index. The index is rebalanced semi-annually.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the investment results of the MSCI USA Minimum Volatility Extended ESG Reduced Carbon Target Index. The underlying index is designed to measure the performance of large- and mid-capitalization U.S. equity securities that reflect the performance of a minimum volatility strategy and, relative to the MSCI USA Index, have higher favorable ESG characteristics and lower carbon exposure. The fund generally will invest at least 90% of its assets in the component securities of the underlying index and may invest up to 10% of its assets in certain futures, options and swap contracts, cash and cash equivalents. It is non-diversified.
merged_description: This passively managed fund seeks to provide exposure to large- and mid-capitalization U.S. equity securities by tracking an index designed to reflect a minimum volatility strategy while also demonstrating enhanced Environmental, Social, and Governance (ESG) characteristics and lower carbon exposure compared to the broader U.S. market. The underlying index selects and weights securities based on ESG criteria, including relative ESG ratings and resilience to industry risks, and applies exclusionary screens for controversial activities such as tobacco, weapons, firearms, and certain climate-related issues, as well as companies involved in severe controversies or not assessed for controversies. Utilizing an optimization approach, the portfolio aims for a lower volatility and improved ESG profile relative to its parent index, which is rebalanced semi-annually. The fund generally invests at least 90% of its assets in index components, with limited flexibility for derivatives or cash, and it is classified as non-diversified.

name: Dimensional - Emerging Markets High Profitability ETF
description_original: The Portfolio is designed to purchase securities of large companies associated with emerging markets that the Advisor determines to have high profitability relative to other large companies in the same country or region at the time of purchase. The Advisor intends to purchase securities of large companies that are associated with emerging markets, which may include frontier markets (emerging market countries in an earlier stage of development).
description_eftcom:
DEHP actively selects large-cap emerging markets companies exhibiting high profitability characteristics, seeking to provide long-term capital appreciation.

DEHP is an actively managed fund that provides a high profitability solution in aim of achieving long-term capital appreciation, whilst balancing risk by allocating investments across various sectors, industries, and countries. The fund holds a diversified portfolio of large emerging market companies deemed to have high profitability, after exhibiting high earnings or profits from operations in relation to its book value. While the fund claims to be market-cap-weighted, the advisor has full discretion to adjust a securitys exposure and increase or decrease emphasis on (or exclude) certain companies after taking into account several short-term factors like price momentum and investment characteristics, which are also the basis for stock selection.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to achieve long-term capital appreciation. The Portfolio is designed to purchase securities of large companies associated with emerging markets that the Advisor determines to have high profitability relative to other large companies in the same country or region at the time of purchase. The Advisor intends to purchase securities of large companies that are associated with emerging markets, which may include frontier markets (emerging market countries in an earlier stage of development).
merged_description: Seeking long-term capital appreciation, this actively managed ETF invests in a diversified portfolio of large companies located in emerging markets, which may include frontier markets. The investment strategy focuses on identifying companies determined to have high profitability relative to other large firms in the same country or region, generally characterized by strong earnings or profits compared to book value. While primarily targeting large-cap firms, the advisor retains discretion to adjust holdings and emphasis based on various factors, including short-term considerations like momentum, aiming to balance risk across different sectors and countries.

name: Capital Link Global Fintech Leaders ETF
description_original: The fund will normally invest at least 80% of its net assets in securities of the index. The index was designed by the index provider to measure the performance of a diversified group of publicly-listed companies considered to be Fintech Leaders.
description_eftcom: The security was delisted. The last day of trading on an exchange is May 22, 2024. KOIN begins its portfolio construction by screening companies from developed and emerging markets using an NLP algorithm. Then, stocks are grouped into two stakeholder categories: Digital Asset Providers (companies that use technology to increase operational sciences, optimize settlement processes, enhance the customer experience, increase data security/integrity and create digital assets) or Solutions Providers (companies that assist in the adoption and implementation of the latest technologies and applications). Index components are selected based on their proprietary sentiment score rankings. Additionally, they are capped in order to limit overconcentration to a certain category and weighted equally. Prior to Dec. 16, 2021, the fund was known as Capital Link NextGen Protocol ETF and tracked the ATFI Global NextGen Fintech Index. It also previously had exposure focused on the blockchain theme.
merged_description: This ETF was designed to provide exposure to publicly-listed companies considered Fintech Leaders, typically investing at least 80% of its net assets in securities of a corresponding index. This index identified companies globally (developed and emerging markets) using an NLP algorithm, categorizing them as either "Digital Asset Providers" or "Solutions Providers". Index components were selected based on proprietary sentiment score rankings, equally weighted, and capped to manage category concentration. Please note that this security has been delisted, with its last trading day being May 22, 2024.

name: Direxion Daily S&P Expanded Tech Software Sector Bull 2X Shares
description_original: The fund invests at least 80% of its net assets in financial instruments, securities of the index, and ETFs that track the index and other financial instruments that provide daily leveraged exposure to the index or to ETFs that track the index. The index measures the performance of U.S. and Canadian stocks that are classified in the application software, systems software and home entertainment software sub-industries of the GICS information technology sector. It is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
SWAR provides 2x daily leveraged exposure to a market-cap-weighted index of US and Canadian software companies.

The security was delisted. The last day of trading on an exchange is April 21, 2023. SWAR is a 2x leveraged bet on the S&P North American Expanded Technology Software Index an index of US and Canadian stocks that are classified in the application software, systems software and home entertainment software sub-industries of the GICS information technology sector. The index is market-cap weighted, and caps individual security weights at 8.5% to provide more diverse exposure to a concentrated industry. Like most leveraged products with daily resets, SWAR is not intended to be held for more than one trading day. For longer periods, the effects of compounding may cause it to drift materially from the 200% exposure it promises to provide to the index.
merged_description: This fund provided 2x daily leveraged exposure to a market-cap-weighted index of US and Canadian software companies. It tracked the S&P North American Expanded Technology Software Index, which includes stocks from the application, systems, and home entertainment software sub-industries of the GICS information technology sector. The index was market-cap weighted, featuring an 8.5% individual security weight cap to provide more diverse exposure within a concentrated industry. The fund invested at least 80% of its assets in instruments designed to provide this leveraged exposure and was considered non-diversified. Due to the nature of its daily leverage reset, it was not intended to be held for more than one trading day, as compounding effects could cause significant drift from the target exposure over longer periods. The fund was delisted, with its last day of trading being April 21, 2023.

name: Nuveen Short-Term REIT ETF
description_original: The fund invests at least 80% of the sum of its net assets and the amount of any borrowings for investment purposes in REITs. The index is a subset of the Dow Jones U.S. Select REIT Index, which generally includes equity REITs traded on a national securities exchange in the U.S. that derive at least 75% of their total revenue from the ownership and operation of real estate assets and that have a minimum total market capitalization of $200 million at the time of their inclusion. It is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
NURE tracks an index composed of U.S. REITs that typically have shorter-term lease durations than average.

NURE`s indexa subset of the Dow Jones U.S. Select REIT Indexfocuses on REITs with short-term lease agreements. Specifically, the fund selects REITs that hold apartment buildings, hotels, self-storage facilities, and manufactured homes. Selected REITs are weighted by float-adjusted market capitalization, with no single holding comprising more than 5% of the index at each rebalance date.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks to track the investment results of the Dow Jones U.S. Select Short-Term REIT Index. The fund invests at least 80% of the sum of its net assets and the amount of any borrowings for investment purposes in REITs. The index is a subset of the Dow Jones U.S. Select REIT Index, which generally includes equity REITs traded on a national securities exchange in the U.S. that derive at least 75% of their total revenue from the ownership and operation of real estate assets and that have a minimum total market capitalization of $200 million at the time of their inclusion. It is non-diversified.
merged_description: This ETF seeks to track the performance of the Dow Jones U.S. Select Short-Term REIT Index, which comprises U.S. equity REITs focused on properties with typically shorter lease durations than average. The fund invests at least 80% of its net assets plus borrowings in REITs holding assets such as apartment buildings, hotels, self-storage facilities, and manufactured homes. These REITs are selected from the broader Dow Jones U.S. Select REIT Index universe and are weighted by float-adjusted market capitalization, with individual holdings capped at 5% at each rebalance. The ETF is classified as non-diversified.

name: ProShares Ultra Telecommunications
description_original: The fund invests in financial instruments that ProShare Advisors believes, in combination, should produce daily returns consistent with the fund's investment objective. The index is designed to measure the stock performance of U.S. companies in the telecommunications sector. The fund is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
LTL provides 2x exposure to a market-cap-weighted index of US fixed-line and mobile telephone companies.

LTL provides 2x leveraged exposure to the Dow Jones US Select Telecommunications Index, a market-cap-weighted index of US telecom companies. Specifically, it holds a concentrated portfolio of firms involved in fixed line (regional and long-distance) and mobile telephone services (cellular, satellite, and paging). As a geared product with 2x factor that rebalances daily, LTL is not a buy-and-hold ETF, its a short-term tactical instrument. As a result, long-term returns can vary significantly from those of the underlying index due to daily compounding. Prior to March 20, 2023, the fund was called ProShares Ultra Telecommunications that tracked the Dow Jones U.S. Select Telecommunications Index.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks daily investment results, before fees and expenses, that correspond to two times (2x) the daily performance of the S&P Communication Services Select Sector Index. The index is designed to measure the performance of communication services companies included in the S&P 500 Index. Under normal circumstances, the fund will obtain leveraged exposure to at least 80% of its total assets in components of the index or in instruments with similar economic characteristics. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This ETF seeks daily investment results corresponding to two times the daily performance of the S&P Communication Services Select Sector Index, before fees and expenses. It aims to provide this 2x daily leveraged exposure by investing in financial instruments and components of the index or instruments with similar economic characteristics. The underlying index tracks communication services companies included in the S&P 500. Maintaining a concentrated, non-diversified portfolio, the fund has historically held a significant focus on telecommunications companies within this sector. Due to its 2x daily leverage and daily rebalancing, it is designed for short-term tactical use and is not suitable for buy-and-hold strategies, as long-term returns can differ significantly from the underlying index due to daily compounding.

name: ProShares Ultra Consumer Services
description_original: The fund invests in financial instruments that ProShare Advisors believes, in combination, should produce daily returns consistent with the fund's investment objective. The index is designed to measure the stock performance of U.S. companies in the consumer services industry. The fund is non-diversified.
description_eftcom:
UCC provides 2x exposure to a market cap-weighted index of US consumer discretionary stocks drawn from the S&P 500.

UCC provides 2x the daily performance of a market cap-weighted index representing the consumer discretionary sector of the S&P 500. The underlying index, which is an S&P Select Sector Index, includes automobiles & components, consumer durables and apparel, consumer services, and retailing. As a levered product with daily resets, UCC is not a buy-and-hold investment, it's a short-term tactical instrument. As a result, long-term returns could materially differ from those of the underlying index due to daily compounding. Prior to March 20, 2023, the fund traded as the Proshares Ultra Consumer Services and tracked the Dow Jones U.S. Consumer Services Index.
description_moringstar: The investment seeks daily investment results, before fees and expenses, that correspond to two times (2x) the daily performance of the S&P Consumer Discretionary Select Sector Index. The index is designed to measure the performance of consumer discretionary companies included in the S&P 500 Index. Under normal circumstances, the fund will obtain leveraged exposure to at least 80% of its total assets in components of the index or in instruments with similar economic characteristics. The fund is non-diversified.
merged_description: This ETF is designed to seek daily investment results corresponding to two times (2x) the daily performance of a market-cap weighted index representing the consumer discretionary sector of the S&P 500. Tracking US companies in areas like automobiles, consumer durables and apparel, consumer services, and retailing, the fund obtains leveraged exposure to align with the index's performance before fees and expenses. Utilizing financial instruments, the fund is non-diversified and structured with daily resets. Consequently, it serves as a short-term tactical instrument rather than a buy-and-hold investment, given that daily compounding can significantly alter long-term returns compared to the underlying index.

name: Xtrackers Bloomberg US Investment Grade Corporate ESG ETF
description_original: The fund will invest at least 80% of its total assets, but typically far more, in instruments that comprise the underlying index. The index generally aims to keep the broad characteristics of its parent index, the Bloomberg Barclays US Corporate Index (an investment grade corporate bond universe), resulting in a broad investment grade fixed income market exposure with ESG aspects.
description_eftcom:
ESCR tracks an index of US investment-grade corporate bonds that are screened for ESG aspects.

The security is being delisted. The last day of trading on an exchange is March 13, 2024. ESCR provides exposure to investment-grade, US-dollar-denominated corporate bonds screened for ESG criteria defined by MSCI. The Parent Index includes investment-grade securities from industrial, utility and financial institutions issuers only. The securities are then screened for high ESG scores. Companies with controversies regarding negative ESG impact of operations, products or services are excluded. The remaining companies are included in the underlying index and reweighted to match the same sector, maturity and rating exposure of the parent index. The index is rebalanced monthly. Prior to May 12, 2020, the fund was named Xtrackers Investment Grade Bond - Interest Rate Hedged ETF, used ticker IGIH, and tracked the Solactive Investment Grade Corporate Bond- Interest Rate Hedged Index. On Aug. 24, 2021, the fund name and index name changed as a result of the rebranding of Bloomberg Barclays fixed income indices to Bloomberg Indices.
merged_description: This ETF provides exposure to a broad universe of US dollar-denominated investment-grade corporate bonds. It employs an ESG screening process, selecting companies with high ESG scores while excluding those involved in negative controversies, to create an index designed to maintain the sector, maturity, and rating characteristics of a standard investment-grade bond market index. The index is rebalanced monthly. Note that this security is being delisted, with its last day of trading on March 13, 2024.

name: Global X Data Center REITs & Digital Infrastructure ETF
description_original: The fund invests at least 80% of its total assets, plus borrowings for investments purposes, in the securities of the Solactive Data Center REITs & Digital Infrastructure Index and in ADRs and GDRs based on the securities in the index. The index is designed to provide exposure to companies that have business operations in the fields of data centers, cellular towers, and/or digital infrastructure hardware. The fund is non-diversified.
description_eftcom: DTCR invests in firms from both developed and emerging markets that derive the bulk of their revenues in Data Center REITs and Digital Infrastructure. These firms are involved in the ownership, operation, and development of data centers and cellular towers. Also included are the digital infrastructure hardware firms that manufacture, design, or assemble the servers or other hardware for data centers and cellular towers. The underlying index uses an algorithm that ranks these firms based on the frequency of specific keywords and will primarily include real estate companies. The resulting portfolio is weighted by market cap, with weight constraints imposed to limit concentration to larger caps. The index undergoes semi-annual rebalance and reconstitution. Prior to April 1, 2024, the fund traded under the ticker VPN and has since removed REITs from its fund name.
merged_description: This ETF aims to provide exposure to the digital infrastructure sector by investing primarily in companies from developed and emerging markets involved in data centers, cellular towers, and the manufacturing of related hardware. It seeks to track an index designed to identify companies with operations in these fields, utilizing an algorithm that ranks firms based on keywords, primarily focusing on real estate companies in this space. The fund commits at least 80% of its total assets to securities found in this index or related global depositary receipts. The resulting portfolio is weighted by market capitalization with constraints to limit concentration and undergoes semi-annual rebalancing. The fund is characterized as non-diversified.

name: iShares Evolved U.S. Healthcare Staples ETF
